{"title_page": "Lon A. Scott", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Lon A. Scott\n| image        = Lon A. Scott (Tennessee Congressman).jpg\n| caption      = \n| state        = [[Tennessee]]\n| district     = {{ushr|TN|8|8th}}\n| term_start   = March 4, 1921\n| term_end     = March 3, 1923\n| predecessor  = [[Thetus W. Sims]]\n| successor    = [[Gordon Browning]]\n| birth_name   = Lon Allen Scott\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1888|09|25}}\n| birth_place  = [[Wayne County, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1931|02|11|1888|09|25}}\n| death_place  = [[Savannah, Tennessee|Savannah]], [[Tennessee]], U.S.\n| restingplace = \n| party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| otherparty   = \n| father       = Daniel Egan Scott\n| mother       = Mattie G. Cash\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| education    = [[Cumberland University]]\n| signature    = \n| allegiance   = {{flag|United States|1918}}\n| branch       = [[United States Army]]\n| serviceyears = \n| rank         = [[Lieutenant (United States)|Lieutenant]]\n| unit         =  \n| battles      = [[World War I]]\n| mawards      = \n}}\n\n'''Lon Allen Scott''' (September 25, 1888 - February 11, 1931) was an American politician who served as a [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] from [[Tennessee]] as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]].\n\n==Biography==\n\nLon Allen Scott was born on a farm near [[Cypress Inn, Tennessee|Cypress Inn]] in [[Wayne County, Tennessee]] to Mattie G. Cash and Daniel Egan Scott on September 25, 1888. His family moved to [[Savannah, Tennessee]] in [[Hardin County, Tennessee|Hardin County]] and he attended the public schools and Savannah Tennessee Institute. In 1915 he graduated from the law department of [[Cumberland University]] in [[Lebanon, Tennessee]].\n\nEngaging in mercantile pursuits, the real estate, and the lumber business, Scott also became a member of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]], and served in that capacity from 1913 to 1917. He served as the Republican minority floor leader from 1915 to 1917. He represented Tennessee in the prosecution of Attorney General Estes in an impeachment proceeding before the [[Tennessee Senate]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lon A. Scott|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=S000181|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=5 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nScott resigned as a state representative to as a [[private (rank)|private]] during the [[First World War]]. He was later promoted to a [[lieutenant|lieutenancy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lon A. Scott|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~adams1895/history-story.htm|publisher=genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com|accessdate=5 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nElected as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to the [[Sixty-seventh United States Congress|Sixty-seventh Congress]], Scott served from March 4, 1921 to March 3, 1923.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lon A. Scott|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/lon_scott/409687|publisher=Govtrack US Congress|accessdate=5 May 2013}}</ref> He was an unsuccessful candidate for re-election in 1922 to the [[Sixty-eighth United States Congress|Sixty-eighth Congress]]. He resumed his former business pursuits and resided in Savannah, Tennessee until his death.\n\nOn February 11, 1941 he died in Savannah, Tennessee after being sick for three months and was interred at Savannah Cemetery.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41086774/nashville_banner/ |title=Lon Scott Dies In Jackson Hospital |date=12 February 1931 |work=Nashville Banner |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226105054/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41086774/nashville_banner/ |archive-date=26 December 2019 |url-status=live |page=19 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n \n{{CongBio|S000181}}\n* {{Find a Grave|8036608}}\n<br/><!--this break is to put visual space between the last information and the following template if needed-->\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box | state=Tennessee| district=8| before=[[Thetus W. Sims]]| after=[[Gordon Browning]] | years=1921-1923}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 67th [[United States Congress]] |state=[[Tennessee]]}}\n{{USCongRep/TN/67}}\n{{USCongRep/TN/67/2}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Lon Allen}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1931 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Members of the Tennessee House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:People from Savannah, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Republicans]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Lon A. Scott\n| image        = Lon A. Scott (Tennessee Congressman).jpg\n| caption      = \n| state        = [[Tennessee]]\n| district     = {{ushr|TN|8|8th}}\n| term_start   = March 4, 1921\n| term_end     = March 3, 1923\n| predecessor  = [[Thetus W. Sims]]\n| successor    = [[Gordon Browning]]\n| birth_name   = Lon Allen Scott\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1888|09|25}}\n| birth_place  = [[Wayne County, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1931|02|11|1888|09|25}}\n| death_place  = [[Savannah, Tennessee|Savannah]], [[Tennessee]], U.S.\n| restingplace = \n| party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| otherparty   = \n| father       = Daniel Egan Scott\n| mother       = Mattie G. Cash\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| education    = [[Cumberland University]]\n| signature    = \n| allegiance   = {{flag|United States|1918}}\n| branch       = [[United States Army]]\n| serviceyears = \n| rank         = [[Lieutenant (United States)|Lieutenant]]\n| unit         =  \n| battles      = [[World War I]]\n| mawards      = \n}}\n\n'''Lon Allen Scott''' (September 25, 1888 - February 11, 1931) was an American politician who served as a [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] from [[Tennessee]] as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]].\n\n==Biography==\n\nLon Allen Scott was born on a farm near [[Cypress Inn, Tennessee|Cypress Inn]] in [[Wayne County, Tennessee]] to Mattie G. Cash and Daniel Egan Scott on September 25, 1888. His family moved to [[Savannah, Tennessee]] in [[Hardin County, Tennessee|Hardin County]] and he attended the public schools and Savannah Tennessee Institute. In 1915 he graduated from the law department of [[Cumberland University]] in [[Lebanon, Tennessee]].\n\nEnngaging in mercantile pursuits, the real estate, and the lumber business, Scott also became a member of the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]], and served in that capacity from 1913 to 1917. He served as the Republican minority floor leader from 1915 to 1917. He represented Tennessee in the prosecution of Attorney General Estes in an impeachment proceeding before the [[Tennessee Senate]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lon A. Scott|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=S000181|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=5 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nScott resigned as a state representative to as a [[private (rank)|private]] during the [[First World War]]. He was later promoted to a [[lieutenant|lieutenancy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lon A. Scott|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~adams1895/history-story.htm|publisher=genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com|accessdate=5 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nElected as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to the [[Sixty-seventh United States Congress|Sixty-seventh Congress]], Scott served from March 4, 1921 to March 3, 1923.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lon A. Scott|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/lon_scott/409687|publisher=Govtrack US Congress|accessdate=5 May 2013}}</ref> He was an unsuccessful candidate for re-election in 1922 to the [[Sixty-eighth United States Congress|Sixty-eighth Congress]]. He resumed his former business pursuits and resided in Savannah, Tennessee until his death.\n\nOn February 11, 1941 he died in Savannah, Tennessee after being sick for three months and was interred at Savannah Cemetery.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41086774/nashville_banner/ |title=Lon Scott Dies In Jackson Hospital |date=12 February 1931 |work=Nashville Banner |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226105054/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41086774/nashville_banner/ |archive-date=26 December 2019 |url-status=live |page=19 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n \n{{CongBio|S000181}}\n* {{Find a Grave|8036608}}\n<br/><!--this break is to put visual space between the last information and the following template if needed-->\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box | state=Tennessee| district=8| before=[[Thetus W. Sims]]| after=[[Gordon Browning]] | years=1921-1923}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 67th [[United States Congress]] |state=[[Tennessee]]}}\n{{USCongRep/TN/67}}\n{{USCongRep/TN/67/2}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Lon Allen}}\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1931 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Members of the Tennessee House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:People from Savannah, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Republicans]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Enngaging->Engaging -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lon_A._Scott"}
{"title_page": "Pakistan Muslim League (N)", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani political party}}\n{{EngvarB|date of rebirth=September 2013 - died: July 2018|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Pakistan Muslim League (N)\n| abbreviation = PML (N)\n| logo = Pakistan Muslim League Nawaz logo.svg\n| colorcode = {{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}\n| chairman = [[Raja Zafar ul Haq]]\n| president = [[Shehbaz Sharif]]<ref name=\"persondisqualified6263\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1390816/person-disqualified-under-articles-62-63-ineligible-to-head-political-party-sc-rules |title='Person disqualified under Articles 62, 63 ineligible to head political party,' SC rules |last=Bhatti |first=Haseeb |website=Dawn |access-date=21 February 2018 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180221201158/https://www.dawn.com/news/1390816/person-disqualified-under-articles-62-63-ineligible-to-head-political-party-sc-rules |archivedate=21 February 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| secretary_general = [[Ahsan Iqbal]]\n| spokesperson = [[Maryam Aurangzeb]]\n| ideology = [[Conservatism in Pakistan|Conservatism]]<ref>{{cite news|work=[[CNN]]|title=Pakistan's political parties explained|date=18 February 2008|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/asiapcf/02/15/pakistan.parties/index.html}}</ref><br>[[Pragmatism]]<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Al-Jazeera]]|title=Explainer: Pakistan's main political parties|date=6 May 2013|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/spotlight/pakistan-elections/2013/04/20134277479966662.html}}</ref><br>[[Pakistani nationalism]]\n| headquarters = 180-H Model Town, [[Lahore]]\n| international = \n| website = [http://pmln.org/ PMLN Official]\n| country = Pakistan\n| native_name = {{Nastaliq|\u067e\u0627\u06a9\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646  \u0645\u0633\u0644\u0645 \u0644\u06cc\u06af (\u0646)}}\n''or''  {{Nastaliq| \u0646 \u0644\u06cc\u06af }}\n| lang1 = \n| name_lang1 = \n| leader2_title = [[Senate of Pakistan|Leader in Senate]]\n| leader2_name = [[Mushahid Hussain Syed]]\n| leader3_title = [[National Assembly of Pakistan|Leader in Assembly]]\n| leader3_name = [[Khawaja Muhammad Asif]]\n| dissolved = \n| founder = [[Muhammad Nawaz Sharif]]\n| merger = \n| split = \n| predecessor = [[Islami Jamhoori Ittehad]]\n| newspaper = \n| wing1_title = \n| wing1 = \n| membership_year = \n| membership = \n| position = [[Centre-right politics|Centre-right]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Sharif declares victory for his party in Pakistan vote |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=12 May 2013 |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/sharif-declares-victory-for-his-party-in-pakistan-vote/story-E9DADY2PUh57OCK5g3Fg2J.html |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812095306/http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/sharif-declares-victory-for-his-party-in-pakistan-vote/story-E9DADY2PUh57OCK5g3Fg2J.html |archivedate=12 August 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Nawaz Sharif declares his party victorious in Pakistan vote |publisher=Al Arabiya |url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/asia/2013/05/11/Nawaz-Sharif-declares-victory-in-Pakistan-election-.html |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512081625/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/asia/2013/05/11/Nawaz-Sharif-declares-victory-in-Pakistan-election-.html |archivedate=12 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Nawaz Sharif Set for Third Term as PM |newspaper=India Times |date=12 May 2013 |url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/asia/nawaz-sharif-set-for-third-term-as-pm-77130.html |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512184044/http://www.indiatimes.com/news/asia/nawaz-sharif-set-for-third-term-as-pm-77130.html |archivedate=12 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| national = \n| affiliation1 = \n| colors = {{color box|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}} Green\n| blank1_title = \n| blank1 = \n| seats1_title = [[Senate of Pakistan|Senate]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|{{PakSen|PMLN}}|104|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[National Assembly of Pakistan|National Assembly]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|{{PakNA|PMLN}}|342|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[Provincial Assembly of Balochistan|Balochistan Assembly]]\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|{{BalochPA|PMLN}}|65|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats6_title = [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh|Sindh Assembly]]\n| seats6 = {{Composition bar|0|168|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = [[Provincial Assembly of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|KPK Assembly]]\n| seats4 = {{Composition bar|{{PakKP|PMLN}}|145|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Provincial Assembly of Punjab|Punjab Assembly]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|{{PunjabPA|PMLN}}|371|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats8_title = [[Azad Kashmir Legislative Assembly|Azad Kashmir Assembly]]\n| seats8 = {{Composition bar|35|49|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats9_title = [[Gilgit-Baltistan Legislative Assembly|Gilgit-Baltistan Assembly]]\n| seats9 = {{Composition bar|{{GBLA|PMLN}}|33|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| symbol = [[File:Pml-n.jpg|100px|center|Lion]]\n| flag = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n{{Nawaz Sharif sidebar}}\n\nThe '''Pakistani Muslim League (Nawaz)''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u067e\u0627\u06a9\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0633\u0644\u0645 \u0644\u06cc\u06af (\u0646)}}|translit=Pakistan Muslam League (Noon)}} {{small|abbr.}} '''PML-N''') is a [[centre-right]] [[Conservatism|conservative]] party in [[Pakistan]]. It was founded former [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]] [[Nawaz Sharif]] in 1993. The [[Party platform|party's platform]] is generally [[Conservatism in Pakistan|conservative]],<ref name=\"Kuperard\">{{cite book|last1=Haleem|first1=Safia|title=Culture Smart! Pakistan|date=2013|publisher=Kuperard|location=London|isbn=185733678X|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AcA-AQAAQBAJ&pg=PT32&dq=pakistan+muslim+league+conservative#v=onepage&q=pakistan%20muslim%20league%20conservative&f=true|format=google books|chapter=The Struggle for Power}}</ref> which involves supporting [[free market capitalism]].\n\nOne of [[Muslim League schisms|several continuing factions]] of the original [[Muslim League (Pakistan)|Muslim League]],<ref name=\"Past Electorals\">{{cite web|title=Past Electorals|url=http://www.pmln.org/past-electoral/|publisher=Past Electorals|accessdate=20 January 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119134852/http://www.pmln.org/past-electoral/|archivedate=19 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the seeds of the party were sown following the [[1985 Pakistani general election|1985 Elections]] when the [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]] [[Muhammad Khan Junejo]] organised the supporters of [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|President Zia-ul-Haq's]] dictatorship into a single party, known as the [[Pakistan Muslim League]]. After [[Death of Zia-ul-Haq|President Zia's death]] in 1988, under the leadership of [[Fida Mohammad Khan]], a large faction split away from the [[Muhammad Khan Junejo|Junejo-led]] [[Pakistan Muslim League]], and formed a [[conservative]] alliance with various [[right-wing]] and [[Islamism|Islamist]] political parties, called the [[Islami Jamhoori Ittehad|Islamic Democratic Alliance]]. The alliance formed a government in [[1990 Pakistani general election|1990]] under the leadership of [[Nawaz Sharif]]. In 1993, the alliance dissolved and the party assumed its current shape, branding itself as the \"Nawaz\" faction of the Pakistan Muslim League after its like, in contrast to the \"[[Pakistan Muslim League (J)|Junejo]]\" faction.\n\nSince its foundation by General Zia ul Haq, PML-N, along with the [[Pakistan People's Party|People's Party]], has dominated the [[Politics of Pakistan|two-party political system of Pakistan]].<ref name=\"Pakistan Election Commission, 1997\">{{cite web|title=National Assembly general election results 1988-1997|url=http://www.ecp.gov.pk/Documents/Results%201988%20-%201997/NA.pdf|work=Pakistan Election Commission|publisher=Election Commission of Pakistan|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828225608/https://ecp.gov.pk/Documents/Results%201988%20-%201997/NA.pdf|archivedate=28 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, after the [[1999 Pakistani coup d'etat|1999 coup]], the party was eclipsed by its own splinter faction, the [[Pervez Musharraf|Musharraf]] - backed [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)|Pakistan Muslim League (Quaid)]], for almost a decade. PML-N regained popularity in [[2008 Pakistani general election|the 2008 general elections]], when it was elected as the principal opposition party. It returned to power following the [[2013 Pakistani general election|elections of 2013]], with [[Nawaz Sharif|Sharif]] elected as the Prime Minister for an unprecedented third term. The party's stronghold is the [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab province]],<ref name=\"Global Security\"/> where it has formed provincial government six times since 1985, thrice under Sharif's brother, [[Shehbaz Sharif]]. As of 2020, it is the main opposition party in Parliament and is led by [[Shehbaz Sharif]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Breakaway from the original PML===\n{{Main|Muslim League Schisms|Convention Muslim League|West Pakistan|East Pakistan|All-India Muslim League|East Pakistani legislative election, 1954|Pakistani general elections, 1970|All-India Muslim League}}\n\nUpon the creation of [[Pakistan]] and departure of the [[British monarchy|English Crown]] in 1947, the [[All India Muslim League|All-India Muslim League]] (AIML) became the [[Muslim League (Pakistan)|Muslim League]], which was now led by [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Liaquat Ali Khan]]. After the [[Assassination of liaqat ali khan|assassination]] of [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Liaquat Ali Khan|Ali Khan]], the [[Muslim League (Pakistan)|Muslim League]] struggled to revive itself, eventually losing control of [[East Pakistan]] in [[1954 East Pakistani legislative election|legislative elections]] to the [[United Front (East Pakistan)|Left Front]].<ref name=\"Scarecrow Press\">{{cite book|last1=Rahman|first1=Syedur|title=Historical dictionary of Bangladesh|date=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham, MD|isbn=0810874539|edition=4th|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bJfcCPUr0OoC&pg=PA284&dq=pakistan+muslim+league+1954#v=onepage&q=pakistan%20muslim%20league%201954&f=false|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> Internal disagreement over the party's direction, lack of a political program, motivation for public reforms, and inadequate administrative preparations and mismanagement all led to the public decline of the party.<ref name=\"PML History\">{{cite web|title=Post-Independence History|url=http://www.pmln.org/pakistan-resolution/|publisher=PML-N Official|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119134828/http://www.pmln.org/pakistan-resolution/|archivedate=19 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> With the [[Pakistan Socialist Party|Socialist Party]], the [[Muslim League (Pakistan)|Muslim League]] struggled for its survival while facing the [[Republican Party (Pakistan)|Republican Party]] and [[Awami League]].<ref name=\"Scarecrow Press\"/> The [[1958 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|martial law]] imposed in 1958 eventually outlawed all [[Pakistani political parties|political parties]] in the country.<ref name=\"Scarecrow Press\"/>\n\nThe foundation and ground base of the PML-N lies with the [[Pakistan Muslim League]], which was founded in 1962 as an enriched conservative project derived from the defunct [[Muslim League (Pakistan)|Muslim League]].<ref name=\"Global Security\">{{cite web|last=Military Desk|title=Pakistan Muslim League (N)|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/pakistan/pml.htm|publisher=Global Security|accessdate=23 February 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102033916/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/pakistan/pml.htm|archivedate=2 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Pakistan Muslim League|PML]] was presided over by [[Fatima Jinnah]], who actively participated in [[1965 Pakistani presidential election|presidential elections]] held in 1965 against [[Ayub Khan (President of Pakistan)|Ayub Khan]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/> After [[Fatima Jinnah]]'s death, the PML was led by [[Nurul Amin]], a [[Bengali people|Bengali leader]], who deepened its role in [[West Pakistan]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/>\n\nOn a [[Pakistani nationalism|nationalist]] and [[Conservatism in Pakistan|conservative platform]], the party engaged in [[political campaign]]s against the [[Socialism in Pakistan|leftist]] [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] and the [[Bengali nationalism|Bengali nationalist]] party, the [[Awami League]], in [[1970 Pakistani general election|the general elections]] held in [[1970 in Pakistan|1970]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/> It managed to secure only two electoral seats in the [[East Pakistan Legislative Assembly|East Pakistan parliament]] and only ten in [[National Assembly of Pakistan|the National Assembly]] of [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/> In spite of its limited [[Mandate (politics)|mandate]], [[Nurul Amin]] became the [[Prime minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] and [[Vice President of Pakistan|Vice-President]] of Pakistan \u2014 the only figure to have been appointed as [[Vice-President]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/> The PML government was short-lived and soon its government fell in the aftermath of the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/> The PML-N is ideologically close to the military and holds common beliefs on [[National Security Council (Pakistan)|national security]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/>\n\nThe list below shows the well-known breakaway factions and their relationships with the military, although many minor factions have existed throughout Pakistani history:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\" style=\"font-size:88%\"\n|+ [[Pakistan Muslim League]]\u2014[[Pakistani military establishment|Military establishment]] [[Civil military relations|civic-military relationships]]\n|- \n! Party conventions !!Year !! Relationship comparison and notes || Founders\n|-\n|PML(N) || 1988 || Pro-''[[status quo]]'', [[Conservatism in Pakistan|national conservative]] ([[Centre-right]]), and pro-[[Pakistani military establishment|establishment]] until [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|1999]]. || [[Fida Mohammad Khan]]\n|-\n|[[Pakistan Muslim League (J)|PML(J)]] || 1988 || Pro-Junejo || [[Muhammad Khan Junejo]]\n|-\n| [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)|PML(Q)]] || 2002 ||pro-[[Pakistani military establishment|establishment]],  Pro-''[[status quo]]'',<ref name=\"Lexington Books\">{{cite book|last=Wilder|first=Andrew R.|title=Elections 2002: Legitimizing the Status Quo|work=Pakistan on the Brink: Politics, Economics, and Society|year=2004|publisher=Lexington Books|location=Lanham MD, Oxford|isbn=0-7391-0498-5|pages=110\u2013120|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CFNtVqYqAwEC&pg=PA112&lpg=PA112&dq=Pakistan+Peoples+Party#v=onepage&q=Pakistan%20Peoples%20Party&f=true|accessdate=12 August 2012|format=google books|chapter=2002 General elections}}</ref> [[liberal conservatism|liberal conservative]] || [[Shujaat Hussain|Hussain]] \n|-\n| [[Pakistan Muslim League (F)|PML(F)]] || 1973 || Pro-''[[status quo]]'', [[Nationalism in Pakistan|nationalist]] ([[Sindhi nationalism|Sindhi]]) || [[Syed Shah Mardan Shah-II|Pir Pagara]]\n|-\n| [[Pakistan Peoples Muslim League|PML(LM)]] || 2012 || Pro-''[[status quo]]'' || [[Arbab Ghulam Rahim|Rashim]]\n|-\n| [[Pakistan Muslim League (Z)|PML(Z)]] || 2001 ||Pro-''[[status quo]]'',  pro-[[Pakistani military establishment|establishment]], [[Islamism in Pakistan|ultraconservative]] || [[Ijaz-ul-Haq|Haq]]\n|-\n| [[Awami Muslim League (Pakistan)|PML(A)]] || 2008 ||Pro-''[[status quo]]'',  pro-[[Pakistani military establishment|establishment]] || [[Sheikh Rashid Ahmad|Ahmad]] \n|-\n| [[All Pakistan Muslim League|PML(P)]] || 2010 || [[Liberalism|Liberal]], Pro-''[[status quo]]'',  pro-[[Pakistani military establishment|establishment]] || [[Pervez Musharraf|Musharraf]]\n|-\n|[[Pakistan Muslim League (Jinnah)|PML(J)]] || 1995 || [[Libertarianism|Libertarian]], Pro-''[[status quo]]'', anti-[[Pakistani military establishment|establishment]] || [[Manzoor Wattoo|Wattoo]]\n\n|-\n! Party conventions !!Year !! Relationship comparison and notes !! Current \n|-\n|[[All-India Muslim League|AIML]] || 1906 || Devolved into [[Muslim League (Pakistan)|Muslim League]], legal personality is presently continued and bestowed by the PML(N) || '''No.'''\n|-\n|[[Pakistan Muslim League|PML]] || 1962||  Large part of the party led by the PML(N), other parts of the party are divided into smaller factions || '''Yes'''\n|-\n|[[Convention Muslim League|CML]] || 1965||  Merged with PML(N) || '''No'''\n|-\n|[[Council Muslim League|CML]] || 1967|| Merged with PML(N) || '''No'''\n|-\n|[[Muslim League (Qayyum)|ML(Q)]] ||1970 || Merged with PML(N) ||'''No'''\n|}\n\n===Electoral history===\n{{Main|Pakistan National Alliance|Pakistani general election, 1977}}\n[[File:Young Leaguy Worker.JPG|thumb|Young League Worker]]\n\nThe [[Pakistan Muslim League]] went into a political abyss after the death of [[Nurul Amin]] and during the [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]] government of Prime Minister [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]].<ref name=\"PML History\" /> It made a strong comeback in response to Bhutto's [[Nationalization in Pakistan|nationalisation program]] in the 1970s. Influential young activists, including [[Nawaz Sharif]], [[Javed Hashmi]], [[Raja Zafar ul Haq|Zafar-ul-Haq]], and [[Chaudhry Shujaat Hussain|Shujaat Hussain]], ascended as the leaders of the party and started their political career through the Muslim League.<ref name=\"PML History\"/>\n\nThe party became an integral part of the nine-party alliance, [[Pakistan National Alliance|PNA]], against the [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]], and campaigned against the PPP in the [[1977 Pakistani general election|1977 general elections]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/> They campaigned on a right-wing platform and raised conservative slogans in the 1977 general elections. The PML, including Sharif and Hussain, were a conglomerate of diverse views and had provided large capital for the Muslim League's financial expenses.<ref name=\"PML History\"/> It was at this time that the party was revived and joined the anti-Bhutto PNA with [[Syed Shah Mardan Shah-II|Pir Pagara]], an influential Sindhi conservative figure, as its elected president.\n\nAfter the [[Operation Fair Play|martial law]] of 1977, the party reassessed itself and saw the rise of the powerful oligarch bloc led by [[Chaudhry Zahoor Elahi|Zahoor Illahi]], who was the main PML leader. After the [[1984 Pakistani Islamisation programme referendum|1984 referendum]], President Zia-ul-Haq had become the country's elected president.<ref name=\"PML History\"/> During the [[1985 Pakistani general election|1985 general election]], a new PML-N emerged on the country's political scene.<ref name=\"PML History\"/> The party had supported the presidency of [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]] and won his support to appoint [[Mohammad Khan Junejo]] to the office of Prime Minister. [[Mian Mohammad Nawaz Sharif|Nawaz Sharif]] had won the favour and support of President Zia-ul-Haq, who approved his appointment as [[Chief Minister of Punjab, Pakistan|Chief Minister]] of [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab Province]] in 1985.<ref name=\"PML History\"/>\n\n====1988 general elections====\n{{Main|1988 Pakistani general election|Islamic Democratic Alliance}}\nThe modern history of the party began during the [[1988 Pakistani general election|1988 parliamentary elections]], when the Pakistan Muslim League, led by former prime minister [[Mohammed Khan Junejo]], split into two factions: one was led by [[Fida Mohammad Khan]] and [[Nawaz Sharif]], the then [[Chief Minister of Punjab, Pakistan|chief minister]] of [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab Province]], and the other by [[Mohammed Khan Junejo|Junejo]] (who later founded the [[Pakistan Muslim League (F)]]).\n\nIn 1988, the Pakistan Muslim League (N) was founded and established by [[Fida Mohammad Khan]], an original [[Pakistan Movement]] [[:Category:Pakistan Movement activists|activist]], who became the party's founding president, whilst Nawaz Sharif became its first secretary-general. The party is not the original [[All-India Muslim League|Muslim League]], but is accepted as its continuing legal successor.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pre-Independence|url=http://www.pmln.org/pre-independence/|publisher=PML-N Official|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119130343/http://www.pmln.org/pre-independence/|archivedate=19 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of the 1988 elections, the PML was part of the eight-party [[Islamic Democratic Alliance]] (IDA), which had contained the right-wing conservative mass as one entity against the left-wing circles, led by the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] (PPP).<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> The general elections of 1988 marked the emergence of the Pakistan Peoples Party's as the single largest political party, with its election to 94 of 237 seats in the [[Pakistan Parliament|state parliament]].<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> The IDA occupied 55 seats, but an influential leader, [[Nawaz Sharif]], chose to serve the [[Chief Minister of Punjab, Pakistan|Chief Minister]] of [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab Province]].<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> With [[Benazir Bhutto]] elevated to the post [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]], the IDA nominated [[Khan Abdul Wali Khan|Abdul Wali Khan]] as a compromise candidate for [[Leader of the Opposition (Pakistan)|opposition leader]] in the state parliament. Within 20 months, tales of bad governance and corruption plagued the Pakistan Peoples Party's government.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> Finally, in 1990, [[President of Pakistan|President]] [[Ghulam Ishaq Khan]] charged the PPP government with corruption and lack of governance and dismissed the National Assembly and the first Bhutto government.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/>\n\n====1990 general elections====\n{{Main|1990 Pakistani general elections}}\nThe PML-N was still part of the [[Islami Jamhoori Ittehad]] (IDA) and participated, under the leadership of [[Nawaz Sharif]], in the [[1990 Pakistani general elections|1990 general elections]]. The IDA competed against the leftist alliance, known as the People's Democratic Alliance (PDA), which had contained the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] and the [[Tehrik-e-Istiqlal|''TeI'']]. The elections resulted in the victory of IDA, with [[Nawaz Sharif]] becoming Prime Minister. Through IDA, the conservative forces under Sharif had a chance to form a national government for the first time in the [[History of Pakistan|history]] of Pakistan. With Sharif taking office, his ascendancy also marked a transition in the political culture of Pakistan \u2013 a power shift from control by the traditional feudal aristocracy to the growing class of modern and moderate entrepreneurs.<ref name='Abdus Samad, Author of \"Governance, Economic Policy and Reform in Pakistan\"'/> For the first time, Sharif launched [[Privatization in Pakistan|privatisation]] and [[Economic liberalisation in Pakistan|economic liberalisation]] policy measures, and his economic team actually implemented some of the serious economic liberalisation and privatisation measures previous governments had merely talked about.<ref name='Abdus Samad, Author of \"Governance, Economic Policy and Reform in Pakistan\"'>{{cite web |last=Samad |first=Abdus |title=The Economic Policies of the first Nawaz Sharif Government 1990\u201393 |url=http://users.erols.com/ziqbal/nh8.htm |accessdate=6 August 2012 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609124627/http://users.erols.com/ziqbal/nh8.htm |archivedate=9 June 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nElection results also showed liberals, the [[Muttahida Qaumi Movement|MQM]], emerging as the third major party with 15 seats.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> For the first time in the history of the country, Sharif allowed foreign money exchange to be transacted through private money changers.<ref name='Abdus Samad, Author of \"Governance, Economic Policy and Reform in Pakistan\"'/> While internationally acclaimed, his policies were condemned by the [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]]. [[Benazir Bhutto]] mounted pressure on President Ghulam Ishaq Khan, who dismissed the IDA government on 18 April 1993.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> The PML-N appealed to the [[Supreme Court of Pakistan|Supreme Court]], which then restored Sharif's government on 26 May. The [[Pakistan Armed Forces|country's armed forces]] and the military leadership attempted to negotiate with Sharif and get him to step down.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> This culminated in the resignation of Nawaz Sharif, and President Ghulam Ishaq Khan was also removed from office.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/>\n\n====1993 elections and opposition====\n{{Main|1993 Pakistani general elections}}\nThe PML-N gained national prominence in the [[1993 Pakistani general election|1993 parliamentary elections]] and occupied 73 seats in the state parliament. The party asserted its role as opposition to the Pakistan Peoples Party.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> The PML-N [[Corruption charges against Benazir Bhutto|charged]] Benazir Bhutto with corruption, stagnation, and endangering national security.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> The [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]] also suffered due to internal factions, one of which was led by [[Murtaza Bhutto]]. The controversial murder of [[Murtaza Bhutto]] by [[Sindh Police]] and the pressure on MQM further weakened Benazir Bhutto. The PML-N and Sharif himself were shocked when they learned the news of Benazir Bhutto's dismissal. An ironic aspect of this dismissal was that it was prompted by the then-President [[Farooq Leghari]], a trusted lieutenant of Benazir, who sent her to the presidency as a safeguard for the PPP's government after the office was vacated by Ghulam Ishaq Khan.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> During that movement, Nawaz Sharif travelled through the length and breadth of Pakistan. He also embarked on a train march from Lahore to Peshawar as part of his campaign to oust Benazir.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/>\n\nDuring this time, the party was among the closest to the [[Pakistan Civil Services|civil bureaucracy]] and the [[Pakistan Armed Forces]], and had close ties and influence in the Pakistan Armed Forces' appointments as well as their military strategies.<ref name=\"The Economist\">{{cite web|last=Editorial|title=Pakistan Muslim League|url=http://www.economist.com/node/12253224|work=September 24, 2008|publisher=The Economist|url-access=subscription |accessdate=23 February 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015163849/http://www.economist.com/node/12253224|archivedate=15 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====1997 elections and power politics====\n{{Main|1993 Pakistani general elections|Indo-Pakistani War of 1999|Chagai-I|Pokhran-II|Chagai-II|Atlantique Incident|1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|PIA Flight 544}}\n[[File:Nawaz Sharif detail, 981203-D-9880W-117.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Nawaz Sharif]], the first PML-N Prime Minister.]]\nThe Pakistan Muslim League (N) struck its remarkable, biggest, and most notable achievement in the [[1997 Pakistani general election|1997 parliamentary elections]], held on 3 February 1997.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\">{{cite web|last=Story of Pakistan|title=Nawaz Sharif becomes Prime Minister|url=http://storyofpakistan.com/nawaz-sharif-becomes-prime-minister-2?artid=a088|publisher=Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920201755/http://storyofpakistan.com/nawaz-sharif-becomes-prime-minister-2?artid=a088|archivedate=20 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It secured a [[two-thirds majority]] in the [[Pakistan Parliament]], the only political party to have gained a two-thirds majority since the country's independence in 1947.<ref name=\"Pakistan Election Commission, 1997\"/> During this time, the PML-N was the largest conservative party, with its members occupying 137 seats out of 207, roughly 66.2%.<ref name=\"Pakistan Election Commission, 1997\"/> In 1997, the party secured its win with an overwhelming mandate, with only a small opposition.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> On 18 February 1997, when Nawaz Sharif obtained a vote of confidence, the Pakistan Muslim League assumed the government of Pakistan.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> Nawaz Sharif allowed Benazir Bhutto to hold the office of [[Leader of the Opposition (Pakistan)|Leader of the Opposition]], though the PML-N held control of the state parliament.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> The PML-N government passed the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan|Thirteenth]] and the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan|Fourteenth Amendment]]s to the [[Constitution of Pakistan]] to stabilize its mandate and strengthen its position.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/>\n\nIn 1998, the law and order situation came under the PML-N's control and economic recovery was also secured.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> A number of constitutional amendments were made to make the country a parliamentary democracy.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> In May 1998, the PML-N government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif ordered six nuclear tests, in response to Indian nuclear tests.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> The tests were extremely popular and PML-N's image and prestige rose to a record level at home.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> However, in 1998, the PML-N government effectively dismissed general [[General Jehangir Karamat|Jehangir Karamat]] (see [[Nawaz Sharif#Dismissal of General Jehangir Karamat|Dismissal of General Jehangir Karamat]]), which ruined its public ratings, but marked a perception of the civilian control of the military.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> This type of power politics and the repeated dismissals of military leaders soured the party's relations with the [[Pakistan Armed Forces]] and its public ratings gradually went down.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/>\n\nDespite its heavy public mandate, serious disagreements appeared within the party. Finally, the [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|1999 coup d'\u00e9tat]] ended the PML-N's government.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> Controversially, in 1999, the party was significantly divided, further affecting Nawaz Sharif's trial in [[military court]]. No massive protests were held by the party; its leaders remained silent and remained supportive towards the military action against Nawaz Sharif. In 2001, the party was further divided by factionalism. Dissenters formed the [[Pakistan Muslim League]], later called [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)|Pakistan Muslim League (Quaid-e-Azam)]] (or PML-Q), which became allies of then president [[Pervez Musharraf]].<ref name=\"The Economist\"/> In 2001, the Muslim League (Nawaz) formally adopted the name of Pakistan Muslim League-Nawaz (PML-N), also known as PML(N).<ref name=\"The Economist\"/>\n\n====2002 general elections====\n{{Main|2002 Pakistani general elections}}\n[[File:Makhdoom Muhammad Javed Hashmi 01.JPG|thumb|200px|[[Javed Hashmi]] presided the party from 2001\u201305.]]\nAs a result of the [[Kargil War]] with [[India]], the PML-N government had generated frustration within the party and a secret [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)|splinter group]] inside the party united on a one-point agenda with all the opposition parties in 1999 to remove Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif from office. This resulted in a [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|military coup d'\u00e9tat]]. The Supreme Court validated the coup and gave General Pervez Musharraf three years to hold general elections.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} After deposing Sharif's government, the party split into several groups and its size shrunk as many of its members decided to defect to the splinter political bloc. Many of its most influential members, sponsors, and financiers came to defect to the new group that was sympathetic to [[Pervez Musharraf]].<ref name=\"The Economist\"/> This splinter group emerged as the [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)]], which registered itself as a political party with the [[Election Commission of Pakistan|Election Commission]].<ref name=\"The Economist\"/> Sharif was removed from the party's presidency and the position was handed over to Dr. [[Kalsoom Nawaz Sharif|Kalsoum Nawaz]], wife of Sharif. With Nawaz Sharif exiled to [[Saudi Arabia]], the party's presidency was handed over to [[Javed Hashmi]], and the party began to reassert itself in the coming elections.<ref name=\"The Economist\"/> They campaigned all over the country and competed in the [[2002 Pakistani general election|2002 general elections]] for the state parliament. The election polls announced the victory of the [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)]] and the liberals, [[Muttahida Qaumi Movement|MQM]], with PML-Q retaining the majority in the state parliament and brutally defeating the PML-N.<ref name=\"The Economist\"/>\n[[File:Nawaz-Sharif-Long-March-on-Ferozpur-Road-lahore-on-March-15-2009.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A mass rally of PML(N) in Punjab in support of Nawaz Sharif.]]\nDuring the [[2002 Pakistani general election]], the PML-N performed poorly, only winning 9.4% of the popular vote and gaining seats for only 14 out of 272 elected members, the worst defeat since its inception in 1988.<ref name=\"The Economist\"/> Hashmi was removed from the party's presidency after his controversial remarks towards the [[Pakistan Armed Forces|country's armed forces]]. In an indirect party election, [[Shahbaz Sharif]] was elected as the party's new president, and the party's leadership shifted its base to London, England. In 2006, the party signed a cooperative declaration with its rival [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] to outline and promote a new democratic culture in the country. Known as the [[Charter of Democracy]], the document was signed by Nawaz Sharif and [[Benazir Bhutto]] in London, and they announced their opposition to Musharraf and [[Shaukat Aziz]].<ref>{{cite news | title='Democracy charter' for Pakistan | date=15 May 2006 | work=BBC News | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4771769.stm | accessdate=22 February 2008 |url-status = live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071231032534/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4771769.stm | archivedate=31 December 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the [[2008 Pakistani general election|2008 general election]], the party won urban votes and dominated the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab|provisional assembly]] of [[Punjab Province (Pakistan)|Punjab Province]]. They secured a total of 91 seats in the [[Parliament of Pakistan|state parliament]], just second to the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]], which won 121 seats, and the parties agreed on forming a coalition government. The PML-N called for the [[Movement to impeach Pervez Musharraf|impeachment]] of President [[Pervez Musharraf]], and successfully ousted him from the presidency and exiled him to the United States in 2008. However, before long, Nawaz Sharif announced his support for and leadership of the [[Lawyers' Movement]] to restore the [[Suspension of Iftikhar Muhammad Chaudhry|suspended]] famed [[Chief Justice of Pakistan|Chief Justice]] [[Iftikhar Muhammad Chaudhry]] in 2008. In 2011, the PML-N established a branch in [[Azad Kashmir|Kashmir Province]] to participate in Kashmir's general elections.\n\n====2008 parliamentary election====\n{{Main|2008 Pakistani general election}}\n[[File:Hillary Rodham Clinton with Nawaz Sharif.jpg|left|250px|thumb|The senior and integral party leadership meeting with US Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]] and [[Richard Holbrooke]] in 2009]]\n\nAfter returning to Pakistan, the PML-N contested the 2008 general election, demanding a restoration of the judges sacked under the emergency rule put in place by President [[Pervez Musharraf]], and the removal of Musharraf as President. After the assassination of [[Benazir Bhutto]], Sharif announced that the PML-N would boycott the polls, but after some time and conversations with the co-chairman of the PPP, [[Asif Ali Zardari]], Nawaz announced that the party would run in the polls and began to rally in the [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]] areas. On 18 February 2008, after the polls were closed and the results had been announced, the PML-N gained 68 seats in the National Assembly, just behind the PPP. They announced that they would have discussions on forming a coalition with the PPP, which would get half the seats in the 342 seat Parliament. In a press conference on 19 February, Nawaz called for President Pervez Musharraf to step down. Nawaz and Zardari agreed on forming a coalition, and Nawaz announced that he and his party gave the PPP the right to choose the next Prime Minister.\n[[File:2011 Pakistan National Assembly - Structure.png|thumb|200px|The PML-N is the largest conservative opposition party (darker green in right) in the [[Pakistan Parliament|Parliament]].]]\nOn 13 May 2008, the PML-N ministers resigned from the government due to a disagreement related to the reinstatement of the judges. Nawaz said that the PML-N would support the government without participating in it. Zardari, hoping to preserve the coalition, told Prime Minister [[Yousaf Raza Gilani]] to reject the resignations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-politics-idUKISL23293620080516|title=Pakistan's Zardari rejects ally's resignations|publisher=UK Reuters|last=Haider|first=Zeeshan|date=16 May 2008|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915060615/http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-politics-idUKISL23293620080516|archivedate=15 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 June 2008, the Pakistan Muslim League-Nawaz (PML-N) and the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] (PPP) won three and two by-election seats respectively, in the national parliament. Polls were postponed for the sixth seat in [[Lahore]] due to [[Nawaz Sharif]]'s eligibility contest. A court ruled he was ineligible due to an old conviction, amid a government appeal in the Supreme Court, which was slated to hear the case on 30 June, thus postponing the vote in the constituency.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7476892.stm|title=Ruling parties win Pakistan polls|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=16 May 2008|accessdate=17 March 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316134441/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7476892.stm|archivedate=16 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The two parties also won 19 of 23 provincial assembly seats where by-elections were held. The results did not affect the 18 February general election results in which [[Benazir Bhutto]]'s PPP won 123 seats in the 342-seat National Assembly, and Sharif's party came second with 91, while [[Pervez Musharraf]]'s party came a poor third, with 54 seats. Sharif's Pakistan Muslim League (Nawaz) won eight provincial assembly seats, while the PPP won seven provincial seats.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSISL159890|title=Sharif's party does well in Pakistani by-elections|work=Reuters|date=16 May 2008|accessdate=17 March 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090110122332/http://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSISL159890|archivedate=10 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-06/27/content_8449844.htm|title=Pakistan ruling coalition sweeps by-elections|publisher=Xinhuanet|date=27 June 2008|accessdate=17 March 2012|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918002452/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-06/27/content_8449844.htm|archivedate=18 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 25 August 2008, [[Nawaz Sharif]] announced that [[Saeeduzzaman Siddiqui]] would be Pakistan Muslim League (N) nominee to replace [[Pervez Musharraf]] as [[President of Pakistan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/asiapcf/08/25/pakistan.politics.coalition/index.html?eref=rss_world|title=Sharif withdraws party from Pakistan ruling coalition|publisher=CNN|date=16 May 2008|accessdate=17 March 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091030154549/http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/asiapcf/08/25/pakistan.politics.coalition/index.html?eref=rss_world|archivedate=30 October 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2013 general elections====\nDuring its election campaign for the [[2013 Pakistani general elections|2013 general elections]], the party competed against its arch-rival, the [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]], and another centrist party, the [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf|PTI]]. In an unofficial count, the party secured the [[Supermajority|qualified majority]] in the [[Parliament of Pakistan|state parliament]], the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab|Punjab Assembly]], and the [[Balochistan Assembly]]; it is yet the only party to have secured respectable seats and representation on provisional assemblies of [[Sindh Assembly|Sindh]] and [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Assembly|Khyber Pakhtunkhwa.]] The leader of PML-N, [[Nawaz Shareef|Nawaz Sharif]], won a third term as Prime Minister of [[Pakistan]], the first time this had happened in the history of the country.\n\n=== National Assembly elections ===\n[[File:District-by-district map of vote share received by the PML(N) in the 2018 Pakistani General Election.png|thumb|This is a district-by-district map of vote share received by the PML(N), as of 2020, the largest opposition party, in the 2018 Pakistani General Election.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!'''Election'''!! Presiding chair of the party !!'''Votes'''!!'''%'''!!'''Seats'''\n!+/\u2013!!Government\n|-\n|[[1985 Pakistani general elections|1985]]||{{color|purple|members participated as non-partisan}}||\u2013 ||46.4% ||{{Composition bar|96|200|hex=green}}\n|{{increase}} 96||{{color|green|Government}}\n|-\n|[[1988 Pakistani general elections|1988]]||[[Fida Mohammad Khan]]|| 5,908,741|| 30.2% ||{{Composition bar|56|207|hex=green}}\n|{{decrease}} 40||{{Color|red|Opposition}}\n|-\n|[[1990 Pakistani general elections|1990]]||[[Nawaz Sharif]]||7,908,513 ||37.4% ||{{Composition bar|106|207|hex=green}}\n|{{increase}} 56||{{color|green|Government}}\n|-\n|[[1993 Pakistani general elections|1993]]||[[Nawaz Sharif]]|| 7,980,229 || 39.9% ||{{Composition bar|73|207|hex=green}}\n|{{decrease}} 38||{{Color|red|Opposition}}\n|-\n|[[1997 Pakistani general elections|1997]]||[[Nawaz Sharif]]|| 8,751,793 ||45.9 ||{{Composition bar|137|207|hex=green}}\n|{{increase}} 64||{{color|green|Government}}\n|-\n|[[2002 Pakistani general elections|2002]]||[[Javed Hashmi]]|| 3,791,321|| 12.7% ||{{Composition bar|19|342|hex=green}}\n|{{decrease}}118||{{Color|red|Opposition}}\n|-\n|[[2008 Pakistani general elections|2008]]||[[Nisar Ali Khan]]|| 6,805,324 || 19.65% ||{{Composition bar|89|341|hex=green}}\n|{{increase}} 70||{{Color|red|Opposition}}\n|-\n|[[2013 Pakistani general elections|2013]]||[[Nawaz Sharif]]|| 14,874,104 || 32.77% ||{{Composition bar|166|342|hex=green}}\n|{{increase}} 77||{{color|green|Government}}\n|-\n|[[2018 Pakistani general election|2018]]||[[Shehbaz Sharif]]|| 12,934,589 || 24.35% ||{{Composition bar|82|342|hex=green}}\n|{{decrease}} 84||{{Color|red|Opposition}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Structure==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"float:right; clear:right; width:500px; margin-left:1em; font-size:88%;\"\n! colspan=3 | Party leadership\n!\n|-\n! Officiate/Party office\n! Party bearer \n![[Administrative units of Pakistan|Provincial Representation]]\n!\n|-\n|[[Chairman]]\n|[[Raja Zafar ul Haq|Raja Zafar-ul-Haq]]\n|[[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Vice chairman]]\n|[[Mamnoon Hussain]]\n|[[Sindh]]\n|\n|-\n| [[President of Pakistan Muslim League (N)|President]]\n| [[Shehbaz Sharif]]\n|[[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]] \n|\n|-\n| [[President of Sindh Muslim League (N)|President]] \n|[[Syed Shah Muhammad Shah]] \n|[[Sindh, Pakistan|Sindh]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Senior Vice President|Senior Vice-President]]\n|[[Ghaus Ali Shah]]<br />[[Sardar Sikandar Hayat Khan|Sikandar Hayat Khan]]<br />[[Sartaj Aziz]]<br />Yaqub Khan<br />[[Amir Muqam]]\n|[[Sindh]]<br />[[Azad Jammu & Kashmir Pakistan|Azad Kashmir]]<br />[[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa]]<br />[[Sindh]]<br />[[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Vice President]]\n| Saleem Zia<br />[[Imdad Chandio]]<br />[[Muhammad Intikhab Khan Chamkani]]\n| [[Sindh]]<br />[[Sindh]]<br />[[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Secretary General]]\n|[[Ahsan Iqbal]]\n|[[Islamabad]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Secretary General|Deputy Secretary-General]]\n|[[Attaullah Tarar]]\n|[[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Secretary General|Assistant Secretary General]]\n|Salah-ud-din Tirmizi<br />[[Lieutenant-General|Lt.Gen.]] {{small|(''retd.'')}} [[Abdul Qadir Baloch]]\n|[[Sindh]]<br />[[Balochistan, Pakistan|Balochistan]]\n|\n|-\n|Secretary Finance\n|[[Pervez Rashid]]\n|[[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n|\n|-\n|Information Secretary\n|[[Mushahid Ullah Khan|Mushahidullah Khan]]\n|[[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n|\n|-\n|Deputy Secretary Information\n|[[Khurram Dastgir Khan]]\n|[[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n|\n|-\n|Joint Secretary\n|Abdul Sattar Mandokhel\n|[[Balochistan, Pakistan|Balochistan]]\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |Presidents of Administered Provinces\n|-\n!Officiate/Party office\n!Party bearer\n![[Administrative units of Pakistan|Provincial Representation]]\n!\n|-\n|President\n|[[Shehbaz Sharif]]\n|[[Punjab]]\n|\n|-\n|President\n|[[Hafiz Hafeezur Rehman]]\n|[[Gilgit Baltistan Scouts|Gilgit Baltistan]]\n|\n|-\n|President\n|[[Abdul Qadir Baloch]]\n|[[Balochistan]]\n|\n|-\n|President\n|[[Raja Farooq Haider]]\n|[[Azad Kashmir]]\n|\n|-\n|President\n|[[Shah Muhammad Shah]]\n|[[Sindh]]\n|\n|-\n|President\n|[[Amir Muqam]]\n|[[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n|\n|-\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"| Central Working Committee (Notable activists)\n!\n|-\n|colspan=3 class=\"hlist\"| \n;Executive Members\n:[[Nisar Ali Khan]]\n:[[Raja Ashfaq Sarwar]]\n:[[Raja Ashfaq Sarwar]]\n:[[Muhammad Ismail Rahoo]]\n:[[Shahid Khaqan Abbasi]]\n:[[Zulfiqar Ali Khosa]]\n:[[Ishaq Dar]]\n:[[Chaudhary Liaqut Ali Khan]]\n:[[Naseer Ahmed Bhutta]]\n:[[Javed Malik]]\n:Azad Ali Tabassum\n:[[Sardar Mehtab Ahmed Khan]]\n:[[Pir Sabir Shah]]\n:[[Muhammad Rafiq Tarar]]\n:[[Safdar Mehmood Jatt]]\n:[[Khawaja Saad Rafique]]\n:[[Khawaja Muhammad Asif]]\n:[[Elahi Bux Soomro]]\n:[[Tehmina Sher Durrani]]\n:[[Muhammad Imran Qadir]]\n:[[Ghulam Qadir Jatt]]\n:\n|\n|-\n|colspan=3 class=\"hlist\"| \n;Ex-officios\n:[[Rana Sanaullah]]\n:[[Sheikh Muhammad Tahir Rasheed]]\n:[[Tehmina Daultana]]\n:[[Hamza Shahbaz Sharif]]\n:[[Maryam Nawaz]]\n:[[Rana Tanveer Hussain]]\n:[[Ali Afzal Lilla]]\n:[[Rana Muhammad Iqbal Khan|Rana Iqbal Khan]]\n:[[Chaudhery Saifullah Maan]]\n:[[Mian Hassan Ali]]\n:Zain Ansari\n:[[Dost Muhammad Khosa]]\n:[[Hasan Shah]]\n:[[Shahid Hussain Bhatti]]\n:[[Muhammad Masood Lali]]\n:[[Mian Yawar Zaman]]\n:[[Marvi Memon]]\n:[[Saima Akhtar Bharwana]]\n|\n|}\nThe major function of the General Council Meeting (or Central Working Committee) is to elect presidents and secretaries, while it is also responsible for promoting PML-N activities.<ref name=\"PMLN's Central Committee\">{{cite web|title=Central Working Committee of Pakistan Muslim League-N|url=http://www.pmln.org/central-working-committee-of-pakistan-muslim-league-n/|website=PMLN.org|publisher=PMLN's Central Committee|accessdate=2 April 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505223724/http://www.pmln.org/central-working-committee-of-pakistan-muslim-league-n/|archivedate=5 May 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The GCM's meetings are generally held at the [[Jinnah Convention Centre]] in [[Islamabad]].<ref name=\"News International, Anis\">{{cite news|last1=Anis|first1=Mohammad|title=Elected president PML-N unopposed Zardari has no respect for agreements, charters, says Nawaz|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-13-7702-Elected-president-PML-N-unopposed-Zardari-has-no-respect-for-agreements-charters-says-Nawaz|accessdate=2 April 2015|agency=News International|publisher=News International, Anis|date=28 July 2011|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402193149/http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-13-7702-Elected-president-PML-N-unopposed-Zardari-has-no-respect-for-agreements-charters-says-Nawaz|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nNawaz Sharif was elected the [[President of Pakistan Muslim League (N)]] in 2011.<ref name=\"Dawn, 2011\">{{cite news|title=Nawaz Sharif elected unopposed PML-N president|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/647332/nawaz-sharif-elected-unopposed-pml-n-president|accessdate=2 April 2015|agency=Dawn|publisher=Dawn, 2011|date=27 July 2011|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304042004/http://www.dawn.com/news/647332/nawaz-sharif-elected-unopposed-pml-n-president|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The General Council Meeting raises funds and coordinates campaign strategy, and it has local committees in every [[Provinces of Pakistan|province]] and in most large cities, counties, and legislative districts, but these have far less money and influence than the national body.<ref name=\"News International, Anis\"/> The Central Secretariat and the Parliament Lodges of the [[Pakistan Parliament]] play important roles in recruiting strong state candidates.<ref name=\"News International, Anis\"/>\n\nNawaz sharif has been accused of corruption and involvement in smuggling large amounts of money outside the country, and he was recently revealed by the [[Panama Papers]] to have been involved in hiding money in offshore accounts and companies.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=ABC news Australia|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-04/pakistan-pm-nawaz-sharif-embroiled-in-panama-papers-leak/7298598|title=Panama Papers: Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif asked to explain family wealth following leak|date=4 Apr 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809122100/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-04/pakistan-pm-nawaz-sharif-embroiled-in-panama-papers-leak/7298598|archivedate=9 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Panama Papers and Pakistan PM Nawaz Sharif|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36092356|publisher=BBC|date=21 April 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170114090446/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36092356|archivedate=14 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/15/world/asia/nawaz-sharif-leaves-pakistan-panama-papers-scandal.html?_r=0|title=Pakistan\u2019s Premier Leaves the Country Amid Panama Papers Scandal|date=14 April 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418231009/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/15/world/asia/nawaz-sharif-leaves-pakistan-panama-papers-scandal.html?_r=0|archivedate=18 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Ideology==\n\n===Economic policies===\n{{Main|Economic liberalism}}\n[[File:Lahore-Islamabad Motorway.jpg|thumb|right|200px|In 1997, the PML(N) built the largest and notable [[Controlled-access highway]], known as [[M2 motorway (Pakistan)|''M2M'']].]]\nThe Pakistan Muslim League (N) policies include [[religious conservatism]], [[social conservatism]], [[neoconservatism]], [[bioconservatism]]s, [[environmental conservation]], and most importantly, [[National conservatism]] and [[fiscal conservatism]]. Throughout its history, the Pakistan Muslim League (N) has emphasised the role of [[free markets]] and individual achievement as the primary factors behind economic prosperity, deregulation of all segments of the economic order, and the strong base of capitalism.<ref name=\"Pakistan Muslim League-N Economic\">{{cite web|title=Agricultural and Rural Development|url=http://pmln.org/agricultural-and-rural-development/|publisher=PML-N Official|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911053414/http://pmln.org/agricultural-and-rural-development/|archivedate=11 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1991, the PML-N's government established the [[National Highway Authority (Pakistan)|National Highway Authority]] followed by inaugurating the [[M2 motorway (Pakistan)|''M2 Motorways'']] in 1997.<ref name=\"Pakistan Muslim League-N Economic\"/>\n\nThe Pakistan Muslim League (N) generally opposes labour union management and large-scale workers' unions.<ref name=\"Pakistan Muslim League-N Economic\"/> The party holds that \"prosperous agriculture is the backbone of national prosperity and diversification of the rural economy, by expanding non-farm rural employment, is critical for the alleviation of poverty\". During its federal government, the PML-N successfully privatised the major heavy industries under its planned industrial development programme.<ref>{{cite web|title=Industrial Development|publisher=PML-N Official|url=http://pmln.org/industrial-development/|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911053752/http://pmln.org/industrial-development/|archivedate=11 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Environmental policies===\n{{Main|Environmental conservation|Pakistan Environmental Protection Agency|2011 dengue outbreak in Pakistan|2012 Pakistan fake medicine crisis}}\n[[File:Nawaz Sharif Park, D.G. Khan.jpg|200px|thumb|A national reserve park in [[Dera Ghazi Khan District|DG Khan District]], established by PML(N).]]\nIn 1997, the [[Pakistan Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]] was established by the PML-N government, and its [[Ministry of Environment (Pakistan)|Ministry of Environment]] was one of the most notable government offices to protect national conservation and forestry in the country. In 1997, environmental [[Public service announcement|PSAs]] were regularly paid for by the government to enhance and promote environmental awareness among the public.\n\nHowever, the ministry's environmental policies remain a subject of ongoing controversy, often criticised for ignoring the health of the environment despite the party's declarations. The PML-N's [[Government of Punjab, Pakistan|provincial government]] in [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab Province]] came under intense media, opposition, and public anger after failing to counter the [[2011 dengue outbreak in Pakistan|2011 dengue fever outbreak]] due to its apathy and the inadequacy of steps taken to enforce environmental awareness and regulations. Recently, the prestige of PML-N has suffered after the government's [[Ministry of Health (Pakistan)|Health]] and [[Ministry of Environment (Pakistan)|Environment ministries]] failed to properly inspect the quality of medicines, resulting in major counterfeiting and environmental crises, which put the party's environmental and health policies in great doubt.\n\n===Science and politics===\nThe Pakistan Muslim League (N) is credited for ordering and authorizing the country's first nuclear tests (see ''[[Chagai-I]]'' and ''[[Chagai-II]]'') amid immense international pressure. It is also responsible for establishing the [[Pakistan Antarctic Programme]] as part of its science and technology strategy. Together with their main rival, the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]], the Pakistan Muslim League (N) is also responsible for increasing [[Pakistan and its Nuclear Deterrent Program|Pakistan's nuclear deterrent]] as well as boosting the nation's [[Nuclear power in Pakistan|nuclear power]] growth, first establishing the [[Chashma Nuclear Power Plant]] expansion as part of its nuclear policy.\n\n===Foreign policy issues===\n{{Main|Pakistan's role in the War on Terror}}\nThe party has been long advocated for broader and stronger [[Foreign policy of Pakistan|relations]] with the [[Pakistan\u2013United States relations|United States]], [[China\u2013Pakistan relations|China]], the [[Pakistan\u2013United Kingdom relations|United Kingdom]], [[Pakistan\u2013European Union relations|European Union]], [[Pakistan\u2013Singapore relations|Singapore]], [[Malaysia\u2013Pakistan relations|Malaysia]], and [[Pakistan and the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation|the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]], as well as [[India\u2013Pakistan relations|India]].<ref name=\"Pakistan Muslim League-N\">{{cite web|title=National Security and Foreign Policy|url=http://pmln.org/national-security-and-foreign-policy/|publisher=PML-N Official|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911060501/http://pmln.org/national-security-and-foreign-policy/|archivedate=11 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1999, the party's government successfully signed the ''[[Lahore Declaration]]'' with India.<ref name=\"Pakistan Muslim League-N\"/>\n\nThe Pakistan Muslim League (N) remains sceptical about [[Pakistan's role in the War on Terror|the country's role in the war on terror]], although it is firmly opposed to religious extremism and terrorism in all its manifestations.<ref name=\"PMLN-Extremism and Terrorism\">{{cite web|publisher=PML-N Official|title=Extremism and Terrorism|url=http://pmln.org/extremism-and-terrorism/|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911055544/http://pmln.org/extremism-and-terrorism/|archivedate=11 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While it remains a strong supporter of the United States' financial and fiscal policies, it remains undecided about the military operations on its western frontier to curb militancy, with many PML-N intellectuals regarding the War on Terror as a campaign against Islam.<ref name=\"PMLN-Extremism and Terrorism\"/> During its previous tenure from 1997 to 1999, the PML-N government took a series of measures to control terrorist groups by establishing the [[Anti Terrorism Court of Pakistan|Anti Terrorism Courts]].<ref name=\"PMLN-Extremism and Terrorism\"/> The PML-N's leadership remains an avid supporter of [[Indian-held Kashmir]], and numerous times it had made it clear that the party will \"never compromise this long standing position on Kashmir dispute\".<ref name=\"PMLN-Extremism and Terrorism\"/>\n\n==Leaders==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"min-width:40em\"\n!colspan=5|List of [[President of Pakistan Muslim League (N)]]\n|-\n!Order!!Image!! Presidents!! Year !! Rationale\n|-\n|1||[[File:Nawaz Sharif detail, 981203-D-9880W-117.jpg|90px]] || [[Nawaz Sharif]]|| 1993\u20131999|| First term\n|-\n|2||[[File:Kalsoom Nawaz Sharif - White House - 2013 (cropped).jpg|90px]] || [[Kalsoom nawaz|Kulsoom Nawaz]] || 1999\u20132001 || First term\n|-\n|3|| [[File:Makhdoom Muhammad Javed Hashmi 01.JPG|90px]] || [[Javed Hashmi]] || 2001-2005 || First term\n|-\n|4|| [[File:Nisar Ali Khan.png|90px]] || [[Nisar Ali Khan|Chaudhry Nisar Ali]] || 2005\u20132009 || First term\n|-\n|5|| [[File:Shahbaz Sharif (cropped).jpg|90px]] || [[Shehbaz Sharif]] || 2009\u20132010 || First term\n|-\n|(3)|| [[File:Makhdoom Muhammad Javed Hashmi 01.JPG|90px]] || [[Javed Hashmi]] || 2010-2011 || Second term\n|-\n|(1)||[[File:PrimeMinisterNawazSharif.jpg|90px]] || [[Nawaz Sharif]]|| 2011\u20132017|| Second term\n|-\n|(5)|| ||[[Sardar Yaqoob|Sardar Yaqoob Khan Nasir]]|| 2017|| First term\n|-\n|(1)||[[File:PrimeMinisterNawazSharif.jpg|90px]] || [[Nawaz Sharif]]|| 2017\u20132018|| Third term\n|-\n|(5)|| [[File:Shahbaz Sharif (cropped).jpg|90px]] || [[Shehbaz Sharif]] || 2018\u2013present || Second term\n|-\n|}\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Rise to power with help from military establishment===\n[[Nawaz Sharif]]'s rise to power is attributed to funding and backing from [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] and the military establishment. Former director general of ISI [[Hamid Gul]] admitted that he formed [[Islami Jamhoori Ittehad|Islami Jamhuri Itehad]] in order to counter the power of [[Pakistan Peoples Party|the Pakistan People's Party]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/760219|title=Hamid Gul accepts responsibility for creating IJI|date=2012-10-30|newspaper=DAWN.COM|access-date=2017-01-04|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104164903/http://www.dawn.com/news/760219|archivedate=4 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Operation Clean-up===\n{{Main|Operation Clean-up}}\nNawaz Sharif, during his first tenure as prime minister of Pakistan (1990-1993), launched a [[military operation]] against his own allies in government, MQM, for allegations against [[Jinnahpur|the Jinnahpur conspiracy]]. Later, the ISPR denied any knowledge of the Jinnahpur conspiracy and separatist maps, which were highly publicized in the media prior to the operation's launch. Thousands of MQM activists were killed, its leadership arrested, and its head, [[Altaf Hussain (Pakistani politician)|Altaf Hussain]], fled to exile in the UK.\n\n===Operation 1998===\nDuring his second term as prime minister (1997-1999), Nawaz Sharif again launched an operation against MQM, who were again in alliance in Sharif's government, on accusations of assassinating [[Hakim Said|Hakeem Said]]. Due to MQM's militant activities and sectarian killings in Karachi, Nawaz Sharif was forced to end the alliance with MQM for the benefit of the nation. An elected PMLN Sindh government in alliance with MQM was dismissed and President's rule was imposed. The operation launched a new era of bloodshed in [[Karachi]] and many party leaders from MQM were arrested. [[Imran Farooq]] (MQM second in command at that time) was forced to flee Pakistan and took political asylum in the UK. Fasih Jugu, who was accused of assassination, was tortured to death by law enforcement officers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/646162-hakim-said-murder-still-shrouded-in-mystery|title=Hakim Said murder still shrouded in mystery|website=www.thenews.com.pk|access-date=2017-01-04|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104164224/https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/646162-hakim-said-murder-still-shrouded-in-mystery|archivedate=4 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The operation resulted in major unrest as the PMLN government tried to nab the criminal elements ravaging the city of Karachi. This was one of the prime excuses the military conjured up for illegally ousting Nawaz Sharif's government in 1999 through martial law.\n\n===Plane hijacking===\nIn 1999, Nawaz Sharif was allegedly involved in the hijacking of a plane carrying then Chief of Army Staff Pervez Musharraf as it was about to land at [[Jinnah International Airport|Karachi airport]], and the control tower ordered the plane not to land in Pakistan but India instead. However, Musharraf and his loyalists had been planning a coup for months and some versions of the story claim that Musharraf orchestrated the coup from the plane and the military didn't allow the plane to land until Musharraf was assured that the military was in control of the airport. The military forced the courts to convict Sharif and sentence him to life imprisonment in 2000. General Musharraf had initially decided to hang Nawaz Sharif but under pressure from the President of the United States Bill Clinton and King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia, he decided not to go through with the plan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/pakistans-deposed-pm-waits-to-hear-if-he-will-be-hanged-279668.html|title=Pakistan's deposed PM waits to hear if he will be hanged|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-06-11|language=en-GB}}</ref> In 2010, The Supreme Court of Pakistan overturned Nawaz' conviction, making him eligible to run for power again.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jul/17/nawaz-sharif-hijack-conviction-overturned|title=Pakistan court quashes Sharif hijacking conviction|last=Press|first=Associated|date=2009-07-17|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2017-01-04|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104165340/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jul/17/nawaz-sharif-hijack-conviction-overturned|archivedate=4 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Allegations of corruption===\nPMLN has been accused of corruption in revolutionary economic schemes such as the Yellow Cab Scheme, The National Debt Retirement Programme (NDRP), the Sasti Roti Scheme, and the [[Nandipur Power Project]]. The charges turned out to be nothing more than accusations by rival political parties to mislead the public. More recently, an international newspaper published [[Panama Papers|the Panama papers]], naming Sharif's sons as among people who created offshore companies. Nawaz Sharif is accused of using corruption money to grow his assets in his business ventures and [[Ittefaq Group|Ittefaq group]], though nothing presented in court so far substantiates these charges.\n\n===Panama papers case and its implications===\n\nThe Panama Papers case, was a landmark decision by the Supreme Court of Pakistan that disqualified the incumbent Prime Minister of Pakistan Nawaz Sharif from holding public office for life.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-40750671|title=Pakistan PM Sharif resigns after verdict|date=2017-07-28|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> The Supreme Court of Pakistan was petitioned by opposition politicians Imran Khan and Sheikh Rasheed, in the aftermath of the Panama Papers leak, which uncovered links between the Sharif family and eight offshore companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/11/pakistan-supreme-court-hears-panama-leaks-case-161101080340730.html|title=Pakistan: Supreme Court hears Panama leaks case|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/01/maryam-safdar-named-panama-papers-beneficiary-170123132820149.html|title=Maryam Safdar named in Panama Papers as beneficiary|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/369465-PTI-lawyer-presents-arguments-in-Panama-Papers-cas|title=PTI lawyer presents arguments in Panama Papers case - Pakistan - Dunya News|website=dunyanews.tv|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> The Court ordered for a Joint Investigation Team to be formed for the inquiry into allegations of money laundering, corruption and contradictory statements made by the Sharif family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1336384/sc-reserves-judgment-panamagate-case/|title=SC reserves judgment in Panamagate case|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2017-02-23|website=The Express Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> On 10 July 2017, JIT submitted a 275-page report <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.suchtv.pk/pakistan/general/item/56626-panama-case-jit-complete-report.html|title=Read Complete Report of Joint Investigation Team (JIT) in Panama Case|last=Desk|first=News|website=SUCH TV|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/353599441/Panama-Case-JIT-Full-Report|title=Panama Case JIT Full Report|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> to the Supreme Court of Pakistan. The report found that Sharif, his sons and his daughter Maryam Nawaz could not justify their income nor their assets, adding that Maryam Nawaz had been proved to be a beneficial owner of Nielsen and Nescoll.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.samaa.tv/news/2017/07/jit-report-recommends-filing-of-reference-against-pm-sons-in-nab/|title=JIT recommends filing of reference against PM, sons with NAB {{!}} Samaa Digital|website=Samaa TV|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> The report also showed that Maryam Nawaz had falsified evidence before the Supreme Court, proven as the Calibri font used in the document did not exist at the time when documents were said to have been created.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1344654|title=JIT report raises doubts about use of &#39;Calibri&#39; font in papers submitted by Maryam|last=Dawn.com|date=2017-07-11|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1344685|title=We asked the creator of Calibri to weigh in on the JIT debate|last=Siddiqui|first=Zain|date=2017-07-12|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> After hearing all arguments and based on evidence provided by the JIT, the Supreme Court of Pakistan announced its unanimous decision and disqualified the Prime Minister from holding public office, finding that he had been dishonest in not disclosing his employed in the Dubai-based Capital FZE company in his nomination papers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1348191|title=Nawaz Sharif steps down as PM after SC&#39;s disqualification verdict|last=Dawn.com|first=Haseeb Bhatti {{!}}|date=2017-07-28|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\nStemming from the JIT investigation, and based on NAB's investigations, the court sentenced Nawaz Sharif to 10 years of imprisonment in relation to the Avenfield Apartments case. The sentence also extended to his daughter Maryum Nawaz, and Son-in-Law Retired Captain Safdar, who were given 7 years and 1 year imprisonment respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1418482|title=Accountability court terms Sharif family \u2018monolith\u2019 in verdict|last=Iqbal|first=Nasir|date=2018-07-07|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\nIn the following election, PMLN suffered a massive blow due to these corruptions charges, with a net loss of 24.35%.<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-44961193|title=Ex-cricketer Khan leads Pakistan elections|date=2018-07-26|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.com\"/> PMLN blamed this primarily on alleged vote rigging and administrative malpractices.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-politics-pmln-analysis-idUKKBN1IC0WH|title=Blow after blow dims re-election hopes of Pakistan's ruling party|date=2018-05-11|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en}}</ref> However, Election Commission of Pakistan (ECP) outright rejected such reports and stated that the elections were conducted fair and free.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1766411/1-ecp-rejects-political-parties-claim-rigging-election-day/|title=ECP rejects political parties' claim of 'rigging' on election day|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2018-07-26|website=The Express Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> The European Union Election Observation Mission said, that no rigging had been found during the election, and polling was termed to be \"transparent\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.theguardian.com/world/2018/jul/27/pakistan-election-imran-khan-official-results-win-coalition|title=EU piles pressure on Imran Khan after Pakistan election {{!}} Pakistan {{!}} The Guardian|website=amp.theguardian.com|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Allegations of treachery ===\nNawaz gave an interview to Dawn News on 12 May 2018 in which he said that non-state actors from Pakistan were involved in the [[2008 Mumbai attacks|Mumbai terrorist attacks]] in 2008. A spokesman for Sharif said that Indian media had twisted his statement to make it seem like he had suggested that the state of Pakistan endorsed and was directly involved in the attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/nawaz-sharif-grossly-misinterpreted-over-remarks-on-mumbai-attack-party-blames-malicious-propaganda-by-media-4468209.html|title=Nawaz Sharif 'grossly misinterpreted' over remarks on Mumbai attack: Party blames 'malicious propaganda' by media - Firstpost|website=www.firstpost.com|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref> A National Security Council meeting was called by the Pakistan Army which declared the allegations were based on lies and misconception without specifically naming Sharif.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1407628|title=NSC unanimously terms 'statement' on Mumbai attacks as 'incorrect and misleading'|last=Hussain|first=Dawn.com {{!}} Sanaullah Khan {{!}} Javed|date=2018-05-14|work=DAWN.COM|access-date=2018-06-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Pakistan|Politics|Conservatism}}\n* [[Pakistan Movement]]\n* [[Liaquat Ali Khan]]\n* [[Pakistan\u2013United States relations]]\n* [[Cold War]]\n* [[Conservatism in Pakistan|Right-wing politics in Pakistan]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{small|{{cite book|last1=Dixit|first1=J.N.|title=India-Pakistan in War and Peace|date=2002|publisher=Routledge.|location=New York, U.S.|isbn=1134407572|pages=504| ref=harv}} }}\n*{{small|{{cite book|last1=Jalal|first1=Ayesha|title=The struggle for Pakistan: A Muslim homeland and global politics|date=2014|publisher=Harvard University Press|location=Harvard, United States|isbn=0674052897|pages=440|ref=harv }} }}\n*{{small|{{cite book|last1=Akbar|first1=M.K.|title=Pakistan from Jinnah to Sharif|date=1997|publisher=Mittal Publications|location=New Delhi|isbn=8170996740|ref=harv }} }}\n*{{small|{{cite book|last1=Ahmed|first1=Akbar|title=Jinnah, Pakistan, and Islamic Identitiy: A search for Saladin|date=2005|publisher=Routledge|isbn=1134750226|ref=harv }} }}\n*{{small|{{cite book|last1=Majumdar|first1=edited by R.|title=Pakistan : Jinnah to the present day|date=1998|publisher=Anmol Publications|location=New Delhi|isbn=8174888640|edition=1st|ref=harv }} }}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Contains Urdu text}}\n{{Commons category|Pakistan Muslim League (N)}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.pmln.org/}}\n\n{{Pakistani political parties}}\n{{Pakistan topics}}\n{{Conservatism in Pakistan}}\n\n[[Category:Pakistan Muslim League (N)]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistani political party}}\n{{EngvarB|date of rebirth=September 2013 - died: July 2018|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = Pakistan Muslim League (N)\n| abbreviation = PML (N)\n| logo = Pakistan Muslim League Nawaz logo.svg\n| colorcode = {{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}\n| chairman = [[Raja Zafar ul Haq]]\n| president = [[Shehbaz Sharif]]<ref name=\"persondisqualified6263\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1390816/person-disqualified-under-articles-62-63-ineligible-to-head-political-party-sc-rules |title='Person disqualified under Articles 62, 63 ineligible to head political party,' SC rules |last=Bhatti |first=Haseeb |website=Dawn |access-date=21 February 2018 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180221201158/https://www.dawn.com/news/1390816/person-disqualified-under-articles-62-63-ineligible-to-head-political-party-sc-rules |archivedate=21 February 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| secretary_general = [[Ahsan Iqbal]]\n| spokesperson = [[Maryam Aurangzeb]]\n| ideology = [[Conservatism in Pakistan|Conservatism]]<ref>{{cite news|work=[[CNN]]|title=Pakistan's political parties explained|date=18 February 2008|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/asiapcf/02/15/pakistan.parties/index.html}}</ref><br>[[Pragmatism]]<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Al-Jazeera]]|title=Explainer: Pakistan's main political parties|date=6 May 2013|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/spotlight/pakistan-elections/2013/04/20134277479966662.html}}</ref><br>[[Pakistani nationalism]]\n| headquarters = 180-H Model Town, [[Lahore]]\n| international = \n| website = [http://pmln.org/ PMLN Official]\n| country = Pakistan\n| native_name = {{Nastaliq|\u067e\u0627\u06a9\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646  \u0645\u0633\u0644\u0645 \u0644\u06cc\u06af (\u0646)}}\n''or''  {{Nastaliq| \u0646 \u0644\u06cc\u06af }}\n| lang1 = \n| name_lang1 = \n| leader2_title = [[Senate of Pakistan|Leader in Senate]]\n| leader2_name = [[Mushahid Hussain Syed]]\n| leader3_title = [[National Assembly of Pakistan|Leader in Assembly]]\n| leader3_name = [[Khawaja Muhammad Asif]]\n| dissolved = \n| founder = [[Muhammad Nawaz Sharif]]\n| merger = \n| split = \n| predecessor = [[Islami Jamhoori Ittehad]]\n| newspaper = \n| wing1_title = \n| wing1 = \n| membership_year = \n| membership = \n| position = [[Centre-right politics|Centre-right]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Sharif declares victory for his party in Pakistan vote |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=12 May 2013 |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/sharif-declares-victory-for-his-party-in-pakistan-vote/story-E9DADY2PUh57OCK5g3Fg2J.html |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812095306/http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/sharif-declares-victory-for-his-party-in-pakistan-vote/story-E9DADY2PUh57OCK5g3Fg2J.html |archivedate=12 August 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Nawaz Sharif declares his party victorious in Pakistan vote |publisher=Al Arabiya |url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/asia/2013/05/11/Nawaz-Sharif-declares-victory-in-Pakistan-election-.html |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512081625/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/asia/2013/05/11/Nawaz-Sharif-declares-victory-in-Pakistan-election-.html |archivedate=12 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Nawaz Sharif Set for Third Term as PM |newspaper=India Times |date=12 May 2013 |url=http://www.indiatimes.com/news/asia/nawaz-sharif-set-for-third-term-as-pm-77130.html |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512184044/http://www.indiatimes.com/news/asia/nawaz-sharif-set-for-third-term-as-pm-77130.html |archivedate=12 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| national = \n| affiliation1 = \n| colors = {{color box|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}} Green\n| blank1_title = \n| blank1 = \n| seats1_title = [[Senate of Pakistan|Senate]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|{{PakSen|PMLN}}|104|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title = [[National Assembly of Pakistan|National Assembly]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|{{PakNA|PMLN}}|342|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats5_title = [[Provincial Assembly of Balochistan|Balochistan Assembly]]\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|{{BalochPA|PMLN}}|65|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats6_title = [[Provincial Assembly of Sindh|Sindh Assembly]]\n| seats6 = {{Composition bar|0|168|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = [[Provincial Assembly of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|KPK Assembly]]\n| seats4 = {{Composition bar|{{PakKP|PMLN}}|145|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[Provincial Assembly of Punjab|Punjab Assembly]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|{{PunjabPA|PMLN}}|371|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats8_title = [[Azad Kashmir Legislative Assembly|Azad Kashmir Assembly]]\n| seats8 = {{Composition bar|35|49|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats9_title = [[Gilgit-Baltistan Legislative Assembly|Gilgit-Baltistan Assembly]]\n| seats9 = {{Composition bar|{{GBLA|PMLN}}|33|{{Pakistan Muslim League (N)/meta/color}}}}\n| symbol = [[File:Pml-n.jpg|100px|center|Lion]]\n| flag = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n{{Nawaz Sharif sidebar}}\n\nThe '''Pakistani Muslim League (Nawaz)''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u067e\u0627\u06a9\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0633\u0644\u0645 \u0644\u06cc\u06af (\u0646)}}|translit=Pakistan Muslam League (Noon)}} {{small|abbr.}} '''PML-N''') is a [[centre-right]] [[Conservatism|conservative]] party in [[Pakistan]]. It was founded former [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]] [[Nawaz Sharif]] in 1993. The [[Party platform|party's platform]] is generally [[Conservatism in Pakistan|conservative]],<ref name=\"Kuperard\">{{cite book|last1=Haleem|first1=Safia|title=Culture Smart! Pakistan|date=2013|publisher=Kuperard|location=London|isbn=185733678X|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AcA-AQAAQBAJ&pg=PT32&dq=pakistan+muslim+league+conservative#v=onepage&q=pakistan%20muslim%20league%20conservative&f=true|format=google books|chapter=The Struggle for Power}}</ref> which involves supporting [[free market capitalism]].\n\nOne of [[Muslim League schisms|several continuing factions]] of the original [[Muslim League (Pakistan)|Muslim League]],<ref name=\"Past Electorals\">{{cite web|title=Past Electorals|url=http://www.pmln.org/past-electoral/|publisher=Past Electorals|accessdate=20 January 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119134852/http://www.pmln.org/past-electoral/|archivedate=19 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the seeds of the party were sown following the [[1985 Pakistani general election|1985 Elections]] when the [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]] [[Muhammad Khan Junejo]] organised the supporters of [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|President Zia-ul-Haq's]] dictatorship into a single party, known as the [[Pakistan Muslim League]]. After [[Death of Zia-ul-Haq|President Zia's death]] in 1988, under the leadership of [[Fida Mohammad Khan]], a large faction split away from the [[Muhammad Khan Junejo|Junejo-led]] [[Pakistan Muslim League]], and formed a [[conservative]] alliance with various [[right-wing]] and [[Islamism|Islamist]] political parties, called the [[Islami Jamhoori Ittehad|Islamic Democratic Alliance]]. The alliance formed a government in [[1990 Pakistani general election|1990]] under the leadership of [[Nawaz Sharif]]. In 1993, the alliance dissolved and the party assumed its current shape, branding itself as the \"Nawaz\" faction of the Pakistan Muslim League after its like, in contrast to the \"[[Pakistan Muslim League (J)|Junejo]]\" faction.\n\nSince its foundation by General Zia ul Haq, PML-N, along with the [[Pakistan People's Party|People's Party]], has dominated the [[Politics of Pakistan|two-party political system of Pakistan]].<ref name=\"Pakistan Election Commission, 1997\">{{cite web|title=National Assembly general election results 1988-1997|url=http://www.ecp.gov.pk/Documents/Results%201988%20-%201997/NA.pdf|work=Pakistan Election Commission|publisher=Election Commission of Pakistan|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828225608/https://ecp.gov.pk/Documents/Results%201988%20-%201997/NA.pdf|archivedate=28 August 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, after the [[1999 Pakistani coup d'etat|1999 coup]], the party was eclipsed by its own splinter faction, the [[Pervez Musharraf|Musharraf]] - backed [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)|Pakistan Muslim League (Quaid)]], for almost a decade. PML-N regained popularity in [[2008 Pakistani general election|the 2008 general elections]], when it was elected as the principal opposition party. It returned to power following the [[2013 Pakistani general election|elections of 2013]], with [[Nawaz Sharif|Sharif]] elected as the Prime Minister for an unprecedented third term. The party's stronghold is the [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab province]],<ref name=\"Global Security\"/> where it has formed provincial government six times since 1985, thrice under Sharif's brother, [[Shehbaz Sharif]]. As of 2020, it is the main opposition party in Parliament and is led by [[Shehbaz Sharif]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Breakaway from the original PML===\n{{Main|Muslim League Schisms|Convention Muslim League|West Pakistan|East Pakistan|All-India Muslim League|East Pakistani legislative election, 1954|Pakistani general elections, 1970|All-India Muslim League}}\n\nUpon the creation of [[Pakistan]] and departure of the [[British monarchy|English Crown]] in 1947, the [[All India Muslim League|All-India Muslim League]] (AIML) became the [[Muslim League (Pakistan)|Muslim League]], which was now led by [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Liaquat Ali Khan]]. After the [[Assassination of liaqat ali khan|assassination]] of [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Liaquat Ali Khan|Ali Khan]], the [[Muslim League (Pakistan)|Muslim League]] struggled to revive itself, eventually losing control of [[East Pakistan]] in [[1954 East Pakistani legislative election|legislative elections]] to the [[United Front (East Pakistan)|Left Front]].<ref name=\"Scarecrow Press\">{{cite book|last1=Rahman|first1=Syedur|title=Historical dictionary of Bangladesh|date=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham, MD|isbn=0810874539|edition=4th|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bJfcCPUr0OoC&pg=PA284&dq=pakistan+muslim+league+1954#v=onepage&q=pakistan%20muslim%20league%201954&f=false|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> Internal disagreement over the party's direction, lack of a political program, motivation for public reforms, and inadequate administrative preparations and mismanagement all led to the public decline of the party.<ref name=\"PML History\">{{cite web|title=Post-Independence History|url=http://www.pmln.org/pakistan-resolution/|publisher=PML-N Official|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119134828/http://www.pmln.org/pakistan-resolution/|archivedate=19 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> With the [[Pakistan Socialist Party|Socialist Party]], the [[Muslim League (Pakistan)|Muslim League]] struggled for its survival while facing the [[Republican Party (Pakistan)|Republican Party]] and [[Awami League]].<ref name=\"Scarecrow Press\"/> The [[1958 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|martial law]] imposed in 1958 eventually outlawed all [[Pakistani political parties|political parties]] in the country.<ref name=\"Scarecrow Press\"/>\n\nThe foundation and ground base of the PML-N lies with the [[Pakistan Muslim League]], which was founded in 1962 as an enriched conservative project derived from the defunct [[Muslim League (Pakistan)|Muslim League]].<ref name=\"Global Security\">{{cite web|last=Military Desk|title=Pakistan Muslim League (N)|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/pakistan/pml.htm|publisher=Global Security|accessdate=23 February 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102033916/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/pakistan/pml.htm|archivedate=2 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Pakistan Muslim League|PML]] was presided over by [[Fatima Jinnah]], who actively participated in [[1965 Pakistani presidential election|presidential elections]] held in 1965 against [[Ayub Khan (President of Pakistan)|Ayub Khan]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/> After [[Fatima Jinnah]]'s death, the PML was led by [[Nurul Amin]], a [[Bengali people|Bengali leader]], who deepened its role in [[West Pakistan]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/>\n\nOn a [[Pakistani nationalism|nationalist]] and [[Conservatism in Pakistan|conservative platform]], the party engaged in [[political campaign]]s against the [[Socialism in Pakistan|leftist]] [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] and the [[Bengali nationalism|Bengali nationalist]] party, the [[Awami League]], in [[1970 Pakistani general election|the general elections]] held in [[1970 in Pakistan|1970]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/> It managed to secure only two electoral seats in the [[East Pakistan Legislative Assembly|East Pakistan parliament]] and only ten in [[National Assembly of Pakistan|the National Assembly]] of [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/> In spite of its limited [[Mandate (politics)|mandate]], [[Nurul Amin]] became the [[Prime minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] and [[Vice President of Pakistan|Vice-President]] of Pakistan \u2014 the only figure to have been appointed as [[Vice-President]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/> The PML government was short-lived and soon its government fell in the aftermath of the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/> The PML-N is ideologically close to the military and holds common beliefs on [[National Security Council (Pakistan)|national security]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/>\n\nThe list below shows the well-known breakaway factions and their relationships with the military, although many minor factions have existed throughout Pakistani history:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\" style=\"font-size:88%\"\n|+ [[Pakistan Muslim League]]\u2014[[Pakistani military establishment|Military establishment]] [[Civil military relations|civic-military relationships]]\n|- \n! Party conventions !!Year !! Relationship comparison and notes || Founders\n|-\n|PML(N) || 1988 || Pro-''[[status quo]]'', [[Conservatism in Pakistan|national conservative]] ([[Centre-right]]), and pro-[[Pakistani military establishment|establishment]] until [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|1999]]. || [[Fida Mohammad Khan]]\n|-\n|[[Pakistan Muslim League (J)|PML(J)]] || 1988 || Pro-Junejo || [[Muhammad Khan Junejo]]\n|-\n| [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)|PML(Q)]] || 2002 ||pro-[[Pakistani military establishment|establishment]],  Pro-''[[status quo]]'',<ref name=\"Lexington Books\">{{cite book|last=Wilder|first=Andrew R.|title=Elections 2002: Legitimizing the Status Quo|work=Pakistan on the Brink: Politics, Economics, and Society|year=2004|publisher=Lexington Books|location=Lanham MD, Oxford|isbn=0-7391-0498-5|pages=110\u2013120|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CFNtVqYqAwEC&pg=PA112&lpg=PA112&dq=Pakistan+Peoples+Party#v=onepage&q=Pakistan%20Peoples%20Party&f=true|accessdate=12 August 2012|format=google books|chapter=2002 General elections}}</ref> [[liberal conservatism|liberal conservative]] || [[Shujaat Hussain|Hussain]] \n|-\n| [[Pakistan Muslim League (F)|PML(F)]] || 1973 || Pro-''[[status quo]]'', [[Nationalism in Pakistan|nationalist]] ([[Sindhi nationalism|Sindhi]]) || [[Syed Shah Mardan Shah-II|Pir Pagara]]\n|-\n| [[Pakistan Peoples Muslim League|PML(LM)]] || 2012 || Pro-''[[status quo]]'' || [[Arbab Ghulam Rahim|Rashim]]\n|-\n| [[Pakistan Muslim League (Z)|PML(Z)]] || 2001 ||Pro-''[[status quo]]'',  pro-[[Pakistani military establishment|establishment]], [[Islamism in Pakistan|ultraconservative]] || [[Ijaz-ul-Haq|Haq]]\n|-\n| [[Awami Muslim League (Pakistan)|PML(A)]] || 2008 ||Pro-''[[status quo]]'',  pro-[[Pakistani military establishment|establishment]] || [[Sheikh Rashid Ahmad|Ahmad]] \n|-\n| [[All Pakistan Muslim League|PML(P)]] || 2010 || [[Liberalism|Liberal]], Pro-''[[status quo]]'',  pro-[[Pakistani military establishment|establishment]] || [[Pervez Musharraf|Musharraf]]\n|-\n|[[Pakistan Muslim League (Jinnah)|PML(J)]] || 1995 || [[Libertarianism|Libertarian]], Pro-''[[status quo]]'', anti-[[Pakistani military establishment|establishment]] || [[Manzoor Wattoo|Wattoo]]\n\n|-\n! Party conventions !!Year !! Relationship comparison and notes !! Current \n|-\n|[[All-India Muslim League|AIML]] || 1906 || Devolved into [[Muslim League (Pakistan)|Muslim League]], legal personality is presently continued and bestowed by the PML(N) || '''No.'''\n|-\n|[[Pakistan Muslim League|PML]] || 1962||  Large part of the party led by the PML(N), other parts of the party are divided into smaller factions || '''Yes'''\n|-\n|[[Convention Muslim League|CML]] || 1965||  Merged with PML(N) || '''No'''\n|-\n|[[Council Muslim League|CML]] || 1967|| Merged with PML(N) || '''No'''\n|-\n|[[Muslim League (Qayyum)|ML(Q)]] ||1970 || Merged with PML(N) ||'''No'''\n|}\n\n===Electoral history===\n{{Main|Pakistan National Alliance|Pakistani general election, 1977}}\n[[File:Young Leaguy Worker.JPG|thumb|Young League Worker]]\n\nThe [[Pakistan Muslim League]] went into a political abyss after the death of [[Nurul Amin]] and during the [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]] government of Prime Minister [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]].<ref name=\"PML History\" /> It made a strong comeback in response to Bhutto's [[Nationalization in Pakistan|nationalisation program]] in the 1970s. Influential young activists, including [[Nawaz Sharif]], [[Javed Hashmi]], [[Raja Zafar ul Haq|Zafar-ul-Haq]], and [[Chaudhry Shujaat Hussain|Shujaat Hussain]], ascended as the leaders of the party and started their political career through the Muslim League.<ref name=\"PML History\"/>\n\nThe party became an integral part of the nine-party alliance, [[Pakistan National Alliance|PNA]], against the [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]], and campaigned against the PPP in the [[1977 Pakistani general election|1977 general elections]].<ref name=\"PML History\"/> They campaigned on a right-wing platform and raised conservative slogans in the 1977 general elections. The PML, including Sharif and Hussain, were a conglomerate of diverse views and had provided large capital for the Muslim League's financial expenses.<ref name=\"PML History\"/> It was at this time that the party was revived and joined the anti-Bhutto PNA with [[Syed Shah Mardan Shah-II|Pir Pagara]], an influential Sindhi conservative figure, as its elected president.\n\nAfter the [[Operation Fair Play|martial law]] of 1977, the party reassessed itself and saw the rise of the powerful oligarch bloc led by [[Chaudhry Zahoor Elahi|Zahoor Illahi]], who was the main PML leader. After the [[1984 Pakistani Islamisation programme referendum|1984 referendum]], President Zia-ul-Haq had become the country's elected president.<ref name=\"PML History\"/> During the [[1985 Pakistani general election|1985 general election]], a new PML-N emerged on the country's political scene.<ref name=\"PML History\"/> The party had supported the presidency of [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq|Zia-ul-Haq]] and won his support to appoint [[Mohammad Khan Junejo]] to the office of Prime Minister. [[Mian Mohammad Nawaz Sharif|Nawaz Sharif]] had won the favour and support of President Zia-ul-Haq, who approved his appointment as [[Chief Minister of Punjab, Pakistan|Chief Minister]] of [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab Province]] in 1985.<ref name=\"PML History\"/>\n\n====1988 general elections====\n{{Main|1988 Pakistani general election|Islamic Democratic Alliance}}\nThe modern history of the party began during the [[1988 Pakistani general election|1988 parliamentary elections]], when the Pakistan Muslim League, led by former prime minister [[Mohammed Khan Junejo]], split into two factions: one was led by [[Fida Mohammad Khan]] and [[Nawaz Sharif]], the then [[Chief Minister of Punjab, Pakistan|chief minister]] of [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab Province]], and the other by [[Mohammed Khan Junejo|Junejo]] (who later founded the [[Pakistan Muslim League (F)]]).\n\nIn 1988, the Pakistan Muslim League (N) was founded and established by [[Fida Mohammad Khan]], an original [[Pakistan Movement]] [[:Category:Pakistan Movement activists|activist]], who became the party's founding president, whilst Nawaz Sharif became its first secretary-general. The party is not the original [[All-India Muslim League|Muslim League]], but is accepted as its continuing legal successor.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pre-Independence|url=http://www.pmln.org/pre-independence/|publisher=PML-N Official|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119130343/http://www.pmln.org/pre-independence/|archivedate=19 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of the 1988 elections, the PML was part of the eight-party [[Islamic Democratic Alliance]] (IDA), which had contained the right-wing conservative mass as one entity against the left-wing circles, led by the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] (PPP).<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> The general elections of 1988 marked the emergence of the Pakistan Peoples Party's as the single largest political party, with its election to 94 of 237 seats in the [[Pakistan Parliament|state parliament]].<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> The IDA occupied 55 seats, but an influential leader, [[Nawaz Sharif]], chose to serve the [[Chief Minister of Punjab, Pakistan|Chief Minister]] of [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab Province]].<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> With [[Benazir Bhutto]] elevated to the post [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]], the IDA nominated [[Khan Abdul Wali Khan|Abdul Wali Khan]] as a compromise candidate for [[Leader of the Opposition (Pakistan)|opposition leader]] in the state parliament. Within 20 months, tales of bad governance and corruption plagued the Pakistan Peoples Party's government.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> Finally, in 1990, [[President of Pakistan|President]] [[Ghulam Ishaq Khan]] charged the PPP government with corruption and lack of governance and dismissed the National Assembly and the first Bhutto government.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/>\n\n====1990 general elections====\n{{Main|1990 Pakistani general elections}}\nThe PML-N was still part of the [[Islami Jamhoori Ittehad]] (IDA) and participated, under the leadership of [[Nawaz Sharif]], in the [[1990 Pakistani general elections|1990 general elections]]. The IDA competed against the leftist alliance, known as the People's Democratic Alliance (PDA), which had contained the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] and the [[Tehrik-e-Istiqlal|''TeI'']]. The elections resulted in the victory of IDA, with [[Nawaz Sharif]] becoming Prime Minister. Through IDA, the conservative forces under Sharif had a chance to form a national government for the first time in the [[History of Pakistan|history]] of Pakistan. With Sharif taking office, his ascendancy also marked a transition in the political culture of Pakistan \u2013 a power shift from control by the traditional feudal aristocracy to the growing class of modern and moderate entrepreneurs.<ref name='Abdus Samad, Author of \"Governance, Economic Policy and Reform in Pakistan\"'/> For the first time, Sharif launched [[Privatization in Pakistan|privatisation]] and [[Economic liberalisation in Pakistan|economic liberalisation]] policy measures, and his economic team actually implemented some of the serious economic liberalisation and privatisation measures previous governments had merely talked about.<ref name='Abdus Samad, Author of \"Governance, Economic Policy and Reform in Pakistan\"'>{{cite web |last=Samad |first=Abdus |title=The Economic Policies of the first Nawaz Sharif Government 1990\u201393 |url=http://users.erols.com/ziqbal/nh8.htm |accessdate=6 August 2012 |url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609124627/http://users.erols.com/ziqbal/nh8.htm |archivedate=9 June 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nElection results also showed liberals, the [[Muttahida Qaumi Movement|MQM]], emerging as the third major party with 15 seats.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> For the first time in the history of the country, Sharif allowed foreign money exchange to be transacted through private money changers.<ref name='Abdus Samad, Author of \"Governance, Economic Policy and Reform in Pakistan\"'/> While internationally acclaimed, his policies were condemned by the [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]]. [[Benazir Bhutto]] mounted pressure on President Ghulam Ishaq Khan, who dismissed the IDA government on 18 April 1993.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> The PML-N appealed to the [[Supreme Court of Pakistan|Supreme Court]], which then restored Sharif's government on 26 May. The [[Pakistan Armed Forces|country's armed forces]] and the military leadership attempted to negotiate with Sharif and get him to step down.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> This culminated in the resignation of Nawaz Sharif, and President Ghulam Ishaq Khan was also removed from office.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/>\n\n====1993 elections and opposition====\n{{Main|1993 Pakistani general elections}}\nThe PML-N gained national prominence in the [[1993 Pakistani general election|1993 parliamentary elections]] and occupied 73 seats in the state parliament. The party asserted its role as opposition to the Pakistan Peoples Party.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> The PML-N [[Corruption charges against Benazir Bhutto|charged]] Benazir Bhutto with corruption, stagnation, and endangering national security.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> The [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]] also suffered due to internal factions, one of which was led by [[Murtaza Bhutto]]. The controversial murder of [[Murtaza Bhutto]] by [[Sindh Police]] and the pressure on MQM further weakened Benazir Bhutto. The PML-N and Sharif himself were shocked when they learned the news of Benazir Bhutto's dismissal. An ironic aspect of this dismissal was that it was prompted by the then-President [[Farooq Leghari]], a trusted lieutenant of Benazir, who sent her to the presidency as a safeguard for the PPP's government after the office was vacated by Ghulam Ishaq Khan.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> During that movement, Nawaz Sharif travelled through the length and breadth of Pakistan. He also embarked on a train march from Lahore to Peshawar as part of his campaign to oust Benazir.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/>\n\nDuring this time, the party was among the closest to the [[Pakistan Civil Services|civil bureaucracy]] and the [[Pakistan Armed Forces]], and had close ties and influence in the Pakistan Armed Forces' appointments as well as their military strategies.<ref name=\"The Economist\">{{cite web|last=Editorial|title=Pakistan Muslim League|url=http://www.economist.com/node/12253224|work=September 24, 2008|publisher=The Economist|url-access=subscription |accessdate=23 February 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015163849/http://www.economist.com/node/12253224|archivedate=15 October 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====1997 elections and power politics====\n{{Main|1993 Pakistani general elections|Indo-Pakistani War of 1999|Chagai-I|Pokhran-II|Chagai-II|Atlantique Incident|1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|PIA Flight 544}}\n[[File:Nawaz Sharif detail, 981203-D-9880W-117.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Nawaz Sharif]], the first PML-N Prime Minister.]]\nThe Pakistan Muslim League (N) struck its remarkable, biggest, and most notable achievement in the [[1997 Pakistani general election|1997 parliamentary elections]], held on 3 February 1997.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\">{{cite web|last=Story of Pakistan|title=Nawaz Sharif becomes Prime Minister|url=http://storyofpakistan.com/nawaz-sharif-becomes-prime-minister-2?artid=a088|publisher=Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920201755/http://storyofpakistan.com/nawaz-sharif-becomes-prime-minister-2?artid=a088|archivedate=20 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It secured a [[two-thirds majority]] in the [[Pakistan Parliament]], the only political party to have gained a two-thirds majority since the country's independence in 1947.<ref name=\"Pakistan Election Commission, 1997\"/> During this time, the PML-N was the largest conservative party, with its members occupying 137 seats out of 207, roughly 66.2%.<ref name=\"Pakistan Election Commission, 1997\"/> In 1997, the party secured its win with an overwhelming mandate, with only a small opposition.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> On 18 February 1997, when Nawaz Sharif obtained a vote of confidence, the Pakistan Muslim League assumed the government of Pakistan.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> Nawaz Sharif allowed Benazir Bhutto to hold the office of [[Leader of the Opposition (Pakistan)|Leader of the Opposition]], though the PML-N held control of the state parliament.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/> The PML-N government passed the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan|Thirteenth]] and the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the Constitution of Pakistan|Fourteenth Amendment]]s to the [[Constitution of Pakistan]] to stabilize its mandate and strengthen its position.<ref name=\"Past Electorals\"/>\n\nIn 1998, the law and order situation came under the PML-N's control and economic recovery was also secured.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> A number of constitutional amendments were made to make the country a parliamentary democracy.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> In May 1998, the PML-N government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif ordered six nuclear tests, in response to Indian nuclear tests.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> The tests were extremely popular and PML-N's image and prestige rose to a record level at home.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> However, in 1998, the PML-N government effectively dismissed general [[General Jehangir Karamat|Jehangir Karamat]] (see [[Nawaz Sharif#Dismissal of General Jehangir Karamat|Dismissal of General Jehangir Karamat]]), which ruined its public ratings, but marked a perception of the civilian control of the military.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> This type of power politics and the repeated dismissals of military leaders soured the party's relations with the [[Pakistan Armed Forces]] and its public ratings gradually went down.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/>\n\nDespite its heavy public mandate, serious disagreements appeared within the party. Finally, the [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|1999 coup d'\u00e9tat]] ended the PML-N's government.<ref name=\"Story of Pakistan (Pakistan Muslim League (N))\"/> Controversially, in 1999, the party was significantly divided, further affecting Nawaz Sharif's trial in [[military court]]. No massive protests were held by the party; its leaders remained silent and remained supportive towards the military action against Nawaz Sharif. In 2001, the party was further divided by factionalism. Dissenters formed the [[Pakistan Muslim League]], later called [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)|Pakistan Muslim League (Quaid-e-Azam)]] (or PML-Q), which became allies of then president [[Pervez Musharraf]].<ref name=\"The Economist\"/> In 2001, the Muslim League (Nawaz) formally adopted the name of Pakistan Muslim League-Nawaz (PML-N), also known as PML(N).<ref name=\"The Economist\"/>\n\n====2002 general elections====\n{{Main|2002 Pakistani general elections}}\n[[File:Makhdoom Muhammad Javed Hashmi 01.JPG|thumb|200px|[[Javed Hashmi]] presided the party from 2001\u201305.]]\nAs a result of the [[Kargil War]] with [[India]], the PML-N government had generated frustration within the party and a secret [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)|splinter group]] inside the party united on a one-point agenda with all the opposition parties in 1999 to remove Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif from office. This resulted in a [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|military coup d'\u00e9tat]]. The Supreme Court validated the coup and gave General Pervez Musharraf three years to hold general elections.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} After deposing Sharif's government, the party split into several groups and its size shrunk as many of its members decided to defect to the splinter political bloc. Many of its most influential members, sponsors, and financiers came to defect to the new group that was sympathetic to [[Pervez Musharraf]].<ref name=\"The Economist\"/> This splinter group emerged as the [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)]], which registered itself as a political party with the [[Election Commission of Pakistan|Election Commission]].<ref name=\"The Economist\"/> Sharif was removed from the party's presidency and the position was handed over to Dr. [[Kalsoom Nawaz Sharif|Kalsoum Nawaz]], wife of Sharif. With Nawaz Sharif exiled to [[Saudi Arabia]], the party's presidency was handed over to [[Javed Hashmi]], and the party began to reassert itself in the coming elections.<ref name=\"The Economist\"/> They campaigned all over the country and competed in the [[2002 Pakistani general election|2002 general elections]] for the state parliament. The election polls announced the victory of the [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)]] and the liberals, [[Muttahida Qaumi Movement|MQM]], with PML-Q retaining the majority in the state parliament and brutally defeating the PML-N.<ref name=\"The Economist\"/>\n[[File:Nawaz-Sharif-Long-March-on-Ferozpur-Road-lahore-on-March-15-2009.jpg|thumb|left|200px|A mass rally of PML(N) in Punjab in support of Nawaz Sharif.]]\nDuring the [[2002 Pakistani general election]], the PML-N performed poorly, only winning 9.4% of the popular vote and gaining seats for only 14 out of 272 elected members, the worst defeat since its inception in 1988.<ref name=\"The Economist\"/> Hashmi was removed from the party's presidency after his controversial remarks towards the [[Pakistan Armed Forces|country's armed forces]]. In an indirect party election, [[Shahbaz Sharif]] was elected as the party's new president, and the party's leadership shifted its base to London, England. In 2006, the party signed a cooperative declaration with its rival [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] to outline and promote a new democratic culture in the country. Known as the [[Charter of Democracy]], the document was signed by Nawaz Sharif and [[Benazir Bhutto]] in London, and they announced their opposition to Musharraf and [[Shaukat Aziz]].<ref>{{cite news | title='Democracy charter' for Pakistan | date=15 May 2006 | work=BBC News | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4771769.stm | accessdate=22 February 2008 |url-status = live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071231032534/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4771769.stm | archivedate=31 December 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the [[2008 Pakistani general election|2008 general election]], the party won urban votes and dominated the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab|provisional assembly]] of [[Punjab Province (Pakistan)|Punjab Province]]. They secured a total of 91 seats in the [[Parliament of Pakistan|state parliament]], just second to the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]], which won 121 seats, and the parties agreed on forming a coalition government. The PML-N called for the [[Movement to impeach Pervez Musharraf|impeachment]] of President [[Pervez Musharraf]], and successfully ousted him from the presidency and exiled him to the United States in 2008. However, before long, Nawaz Sharif announced his support for and leadership of the [[Lawyers' Movement]] to restore the [[Suspension of Iftikhar Muhammad Chaudhry|suspended]] famed [[Chief Justice of Pakistan|Chief Justice]] [[Iftikhar Muhammad Chaudhry]] in 2008. In 2011, the PML-N established a branch in [[Azad Kashmir|Kashmir Province]] to participate in Kashmir's general elections.\n\n====2008 parliamentary election====\n{{Main|2008 Pakistani general election}}\n[[File:Hillary Rodham Clinton with Nawaz Sharif.jpg|left|250px|thumb|The senior and integral party leadership meeting with US Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]] and [[Richard Holbrooke]] in 2009]]\n\nAfter returning to Pakistan, the PML-N contested the 2008 general election, demanding a restoration of the judges sacked under the emergency rule put in place by President [[Pervez Musharraf]], and the removal of Musharraf as President. After the assassination of [[Benazir Bhutto]], Sharif announced that the PML-N would boycott the polls, but after some time and conversations with the co-chairman of the PPP, [[Asif Ali Zardari]], Nawaz announced that the party would run in the polls and began to rally in the [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]] areas. On 18 February 2008, after the polls were closed and the results had been announced, the PML-N gained 68 seats in the National Assembly, just behind the PPP. They announced that they would have discussions on forming a coalition with the PPP, which would get half the seats in the 342 seat Parliament. In a press conference on 19 February, Nawaz called for President Pervez Musharraf to step down. Nawaz and Zardari agreed on forming a coalition, and Nawaz announced that he and his party gave the PPP the right to choose the next Prime Minister.\n[[File:2011 Pakistan National Assembly - Structure.png|thumb|200px|The PML-N is the largest conservative opposition party (darker green in right) in the [[Pakistan Parliament|Parliament]].]]\nOn 13 May 2008, the PML-N ministers resigned from the government due to a disagreement related to the reinstatement of the judges. Nawaz said that the PML-N would support the government without participating in it. Zardari, hoping to preserve the coalition, told Prime Minister [[Yousaf Raza Gilani]] to reject the resignations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-politics-idUKISL23293620080516|title=Pakistan's Zardari rejects ally's resignations|publisher=UK Reuters|last=Haider|first=Zeeshan|date=16 May 2008|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915060615/http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-politics-idUKISL23293620080516|archivedate=15 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 June 2008, the Pakistan Muslim League-Nawaz (PML-N) and the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] (PPP) won three and two by-election seats respectively, in the national parliament. Polls were postponed for the sixth seat in [[Lahore]] due to [[Nawaz Sharif]]'s eligibility contest. A court ruled he was ineligible due to an old conviction, amid a government appeal in the Supreme Court, which was slated to hear the case on 30 June, thus postponing the vote in the constituency.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7476892.stm|title=Ruling parties win Pakistan polls|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=16 May 2008|accessdate=17 March 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316134441/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7476892.stm|archivedate=16 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The two parties also won 19 of 23 provincial assembly seats where by-elections were held. The results did not affect the 18 February general election results in which [[Benazir Bhutto]]'s PPP won 123 seats in the 342-seat National Assembly, and Sharif's party came second with 91, while [[Pervez Musharraf]]'s party came a poor third, with 54 seats. Sharif's Pakistan Muslim League (Nawaz) won eight provincial assembly seats, while the PPP won seven provincial seats.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSISL159890|title=Sharif's party does well in Pakistani by-elections|work=Reuters|date=16 May 2008|accessdate=17 March 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090110122332/http://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSISL159890|archivedate=10 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-06/27/content_8449844.htm|title=Pakistan ruling coalition sweeps by-elections|publisher=Xinhuanet|date=27 June 2008|accessdate=17 March 2012|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918002452/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-06/27/content_8449844.htm|archivedate=18 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 25 August 2008, [[Nawaz Sharif]] announced that [[Saeeduzzaman Siddiqui]] would be Pakistan Muslim League (N) nominee to replace [[Pervez Musharraf]] as [[President of Pakistan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/asiapcf/08/25/pakistan.politics.coalition/index.html?eref=rss_world|title=Sharif withdraws party from Pakistan ruling coalition|publisher=CNN|date=16 May 2008|accessdate=17 March 2012|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091030154549/http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/asiapcf/08/25/pakistan.politics.coalition/index.html?eref=rss_world|archivedate=30 October 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====2013 general elections====\nDuring its election campaign for the [[2013 Pakistani general elections|2013 general elections]], the party competed against its arch-rival, the [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]], and another centrist party, the [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf|PTI]]. In an unofficial count, the party secured the [[Supermajority|qualified majority]] in the [[Parliament of Pakistan|state parliament]], the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab|Punjab Assembly]], and the [[Balochistan Assembly]]; it is yet the only party to have secured respectable seats and representation on provisional assemblies of [[Sindh Assembly|Sindh]] and [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Assembly|Khyber Pakhtunkhwa.]] The leader of PML-N, [[Nawaz Shareef|Nawaz Sharif]], won a third term as Prime Minister of [[Pakistan]], the first time this had happened in the history of the country.\n\n=== National Assembly elections ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!'''Election'''!! Presiding chair of the party !!'''Votes'''!!'''%'''!!'''Seats'''\n!+/\u2013!!Government\n|-\n|[[1985 Pakistani general elections|1985]]||{{color|purple|members participated as non-partisan}}||\u2013 ||46.4% ||{{Composition bar|96|200|hex=green}}\n|{{increase}} 96||{{color|green|Government}}\n|-\n|[[1988 Pakistani general elections|1988]]||[[Fida Mohammad Khan]]|| 5,908,741|| 30.2% ||{{Composition bar|56|207|hex=green}}\n|{{decrease}} 40||{{Color|red|Opposition}}\n|-\n|[[1990 Pakistani general elections|1990]]||[[Nawaz Sharif]]||7,908,513 ||37.4% ||{{Composition bar|106|207|hex=green}}\n|{{increase}} 56||{{color|green|Government}}\n|-\n|[[1993 Pakistani general elections|1993]]||[[Nawaz Sharif]]|| 7,980,229 || 39.9% ||{{Composition bar|73|207|hex=green}}\n|{{decrease}} 38||{{Color|red|Opposition}}\n|-\n|[[1997 Pakistani general elections|1997]]||[[Nawaz Sharif]]|| 8,751,793 ||45.9 ||{{Composition bar|137|207|hex=green}}\n|{{increase}} 64||{{color|green|Government}}\n|-\n|[[2002 Pakistani general elections|2002]]||[[Javed Hashmi]]|| 3,791,321|| 12.7% ||{{Composition bar|19|342|hex=green}}\n|{{decrease}}118||{{Color|red|Opposition}}\n|-\n|[[2008 Pakistani general elections|2008]]||[[Nisar Ali Khan]]|| 6,805,324 || 19.65% ||{{Composition bar|89|341|hex=green}}\n|{{increase}} 70||{{Color|red|Opposition}}\n|-\n|[[2013 Pakistani general elections|2013]]||[[Nawaz Sharif]]|| 14,874,104 || 32.77% ||{{Composition bar|166|342|hex=green}}\n|{{increase}} 77||{{color|green|Government}}\n|-\n|[[2018 Pakistani general election|2018]]||[[Shehbaz Sharif]]|| 12,934,589 || 24.35% ||{{Composition bar|82|342|hex=green}}\n|{{decrease}} 84||{{Color|red|Opposition}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Structure==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"float:right; clear:right; width:500px; margin-left:1em; font-size:88%;\"\n! colspan=3 | Party leadership\n!\n|-\n! Officiate/Party office\n! Party bearer \n![[Administrative units of Pakistan|Provincial Representation]]\n!\n|-\n|[[Chairman]]\n|[[Raja Zafar ul Haq|Raja Zafar-ul-Haq]]\n|[[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Vice chairman]]\n|[[Mamnoon Hussain]]\n|[[Sindh]]\n|\n|-\n| [[President of Pakistan Muslim League (N)|President]]\n| [[Shehbaz Sharif]]\n|[[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]] \n|\n|-\n| [[President of Sindh Muslim League (N)|President]] \n|[[Syed Shah Muhammad Shah]] \n|[[Sindh, Pakistan|Sindh]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Senior Vice President|Senior Vice-President]]\n|[[Ghaus Ali Shah]]<br />[[Sardar Sikandar Hayat Khan|Sikandar Hayat Khan]]<br />[[Sartaj Aziz]]<br />Yaqub Khan<br />[[Amir Muqam]]\n|[[Sindh]]<br />[[Azad Jammu & Kashmir Pakistan|Azad Kashmir]]<br />[[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa]]<br />[[Sindh]]<br />[[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Vice President]]\n| Saleem Zia<br />[[Imdad Chandio]]<br />[[Muhammad Intikhab Khan Chamkani]]\n| [[Sindh]]<br />[[Sindh]]<br />[[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Secretary General]]\n|[[Ahsan Iqbal]]\n|[[Islamabad]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Secretary General|Deputy Secretary-General]]\n|[[Attaullah Tarar]]\n|[[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n|\n|-\n|[[Secretary General|Assistant Secretary General]]\n|Salah-ud-din Tirmizi<br />[[Lieutenant-General|Lt.Gen.]] {{small|(''retd.'')}} [[Abdul Qadir Baloch]]\n|[[Sindh]]<br />[[Balochistan, Pakistan|Balochistan]]\n|\n|-\n|Secretary Finance\n|[[Pervez Rashid]]\n|[[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n|\n|-\n|Information Secretary\n|[[Mushahid Ullah Khan|Mushahidullah Khan]]\n|[[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n|\n|-\n|Deputy Secretary Information\n|[[Khurram Dastgir Khan]]\n|[[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]]\n|\n|-\n|Joint Secretary\n|Abdul Sattar Mandokhel\n|[[Balochistan, Pakistan|Balochistan]]\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |Presidents of Administered Provinces\n|-\n!Officiate/Party office\n!Party bearer\n![[Administrative units of Pakistan|Provincial Representation]]\n!\n|-\n|President\n|[[Shehbaz Sharif]]\n|[[Punjab]]\n|\n|-\n|President\n|[[Hafiz Hafeezur Rehman]]\n|[[Gilgit Baltistan Scouts|Gilgit Baltistan]]\n|\n|-\n|President\n|[[Abdul Qadir Baloch]]\n|[[Balochistan]]\n|\n|-\n|President\n|[[Raja Farooq Haider]]\n|[[Azad Kashmir]]\n|\n|-\n|President\n|[[Shah Muhammad Shah]]\n|[[Sindh]]\n|\n|-\n|President\n|[[Amir Muqam]]\n|[[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n|\n|-\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"| Central Working Committee (Notable activists)\n!\n|-\n|colspan=3 class=\"hlist\"| \n;Executive Members\n:[[Nisar Ali Khan]]\n:[[Raja Ashfaq Sarwar]]\n:[[Raja Ashfaq Sarwar]]\n:[[Muhammad Ismail Rahoo]]\n:[[Shahid Khaqan Abbasi]]\n:[[Zulfiqar Ali Khosa]]\n:[[Ishaq Dar]]\n:[[Chaudhary Liaqut Ali Khan]]\n:[[Naseer Ahmed Bhutta]]\n:[[Javed Malik]]\n:Azad Ali Tabassum\n:[[Sardar Mehtab Ahmed Khan]]\n:[[Pir Sabir Shah]]\n:[[Muhammad Rafiq Tarar]]\n:[[Safdar Mehmood Jatt]]\n:[[Khawaja Saad Rafique]]\n:[[Khawaja Muhammad Asif]]\n:[[Elahi Bux Soomro]]\n:[[Tehmina Sher Durrani]]\n:[[Muhammad Imran Qadir]]\n:[[Ghulam Qadir Jatt]]\n:\n|\n|-\n|colspan=3 class=\"hlist\"| \n;Ex-officios\n:[[Rana Sanaullah]]\n:[[Sheikh Muhammad Tahir Rasheed]]\n:[[Tehmina Daultana]]\n:[[Hamza Shahbaz Sharif]]\n:[[Maryam Nawaz]]\n:[[Rana Tanveer Hussain]]\n:[[Ali Afzal Lilla]]\n:[[Rana Muhammad Iqbal Khan|Rana Iqbal Khan]]\n:[[Chaudhery Saifullah Maan]]\n:[[Mian Hassan Ali]]\n:Zain Ansari\n:[[Dost Muhammad Khosa]]\n:[[Hasan Shah]]\n:[[Shahid Hussain Bhatti]]\n:[[Muhammad Masood Lali]]\n:[[Mian Yawar Zaman]]\n:[[Marvi Memon]]\n:[[Saima Akhtar Bharwana]]\n|\n|}\nThe major function of the General Council Meeting (or Central Working Committee) is to elect presidents and secretaries, while it is also responsible for promoting PML-N activities.<ref name=\"PMLN's Central Committee\">{{cite web|title=Central Working Committee of Pakistan Muslim League-N|url=http://www.pmln.org/central-working-committee-of-pakistan-muslim-league-n/|website=PMLN.org|publisher=PMLN's Central Committee|accessdate=2 April 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505223724/http://www.pmln.org/central-working-committee-of-pakistan-muslim-league-n/|archivedate=5 May 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The GCM's meetings are generally held at the [[Jinnah Convention Centre]] in [[Islamabad]].<ref name=\"News International, Anis\">{{cite news|last1=Anis|first1=Mohammad|title=Elected president PML-N unopposed Zardari has no respect for agreements, charters, says Nawaz|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-13-7702-Elected-president-PML-N-unopposed-Zardari-has-no-respect-for-agreements-charters-says-Nawaz|accessdate=2 April 2015|agency=News International|publisher=News International, Anis|date=28 July 2011|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402193149/http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-13-7702-Elected-president-PML-N-unopposed-Zardari-has-no-respect-for-agreements-charters-says-Nawaz|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nNawaz Sharif was elected the [[President of Pakistan Muslim League (N)]] in 2011.<ref name=\"Dawn, 2011\">{{cite news|title=Nawaz Sharif elected unopposed PML-N president|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/647332/nawaz-sharif-elected-unopposed-pml-n-president|accessdate=2 April 2015|agency=Dawn|publisher=Dawn, 2011|date=27 July 2011|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304042004/http://www.dawn.com/news/647332/nawaz-sharif-elected-unopposed-pml-n-president|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The General Council Meeting raises funds and coordinates campaign strategy, and it has local committees in every [[Provinces of Pakistan|province]] and in most large cities, counties, and legislative districts, but these have far less money and influence than the national body.<ref name=\"News International, Anis\"/> The Central Secretariat and the Parliament Lodges of the [[Pakistan Parliament]] play important roles in recruiting strong state candidates.<ref name=\"News International, Anis\"/>\n\nNawaz sharif has been accused of corruption and involvement in smuggling large amounts of money outside the country, and he was recently revealed by the [[Panama Papers]] to have been involved in hiding money in offshore accounts and companies.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=ABC news Australia|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-04/pakistan-pm-nawaz-sharif-embroiled-in-panama-papers-leak/7298598|title=Panama Papers: Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif asked to explain family wealth following leak|date=4 Apr 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809122100/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-04/pakistan-pm-nawaz-sharif-embroiled-in-panama-papers-leak/7298598|archivedate=9 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Panama Papers and Pakistan PM Nawaz Sharif|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36092356|publisher=BBC|date=21 April 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170114090446/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36092356|archivedate=14 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/15/world/asia/nawaz-sharif-leaves-pakistan-panama-papers-scandal.html?_r=0|title=Pakistan\u2019s Premier Leaves the Country Amid Panama Papers Scandal|date=14 April 2016|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418231009/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/15/world/asia/nawaz-sharif-leaves-pakistan-panama-papers-scandal.html?_r=0|archivedate=18 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Ideology==\n\n===Economic policies===\n{{Main|Economic liberalism}}\n[[File:Lahore-Islamabad Motorway.jpg|thumb|right|200px|In 1997, the PML(N) built the largest and notable [[Controlled-access highway]], known as [[M2 motorway (Pakistan)|''M2M'']].]]\nThe Pakistan Muslim League (N) policies include [[religious conservatism]], [[social conservatism]], [[neoconservatism]], [[bioconservatism]]s, [[environmental conservation]], and most importantly, [[National conservatism]] and [[fiscal conservatism]]. Throughout its history, the Pakistan Muslim League (N) has emphasised the role of [[free markets]] and individual achievement as the primary factors behind economic prosperity, deregulation of all segments of the economic order, and the strong base of capitalism.<ref name=\"Pakistan Muslim League-N Economic\">{{cite web|title=Agricultural and Rural Development|url=http://pmln.org/agricultural-and-rural-development/|publisher=PML-N Official|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911053414/http://pmln.org/agricultural-and-rural-development/|archivedate=11 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1991, the PML-N's government established the [[National Highway Authority (Pakistan)|National Highway Authority]] followed by inaugurating the [[M2 motorway (Pakistan)|''M2 Motorways'']] in 1997.<ref name=\"Pakistan Muslim League-N Economic\"/>\n\nThe Pakistan Muslim League (N) generally opposes labour union management and large-scale workers' unions.<ref name=\"Pakistan Muslim League-N Economic\"/> The party holds that \"prosperous agriculture is the backbone of national prosperity and diversification of the rural economy, by expanding non-farm rural employment, is critical for the alleviation of poverty\". During its federal government, the PML-N successfully privatised the major heavy industries under its planned industrial development programme.<ref>{{cite web|title=Industrial Development|publisher=PML-N Official|url=http://pmln.org/industrial-development/|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911053752/http://pmln.org/industrial-development/|archivedate=11 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Environmental policies===\n{{Main|Environmental conservation|Pakistan Environmental Protection Agency|2011 dengue outbreak in Pakistan|2012 Pakistan fake medicine crisis}}\n[[File:Nawaz Sharif Park, D.G. Khan.jpg|200px|thumb|A national reserve park in [[Dera Ghazi Khan District|DG Khan District]], established by PML(N).]]\nIn 1997, the [[Pakistan Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]] was established by the PML-N government, and its [[Ministry of Environment (Pakistan)|Ministry of Environment]] was one of the most notable government offices to protect national conservation and forestry in the country. In 1997, environmental [[Public service announcement|PSAs]] were regularly paid for by the government to enhance and promote environmental awareness among the public.\n\nHowever, the ministry's environmental policies remain a subject of ongoing controversy, often criticised for ignoring the health of the environment despite the party's declarations. The PML-N's [[Government of Punjab, Pakistan|provincial government]] in [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab Province]] came under intense media, opposition, and public anger after failing to counter the [[2011 dengue outbreak in Pakistan|2011 dengue fever outbreak]] due to its apathy and the inadequacy of steps taken to enforce environmental awareness and regulations. Recently, the prestige of PML-N has suffered after the government's [[Ministry of Health (Pakistan)|Health]] and [[Ministry of Environment (Pakistan)|Environment ministries]] failed to properly inspect the quality of medicines, resulting in major counterfeiting and environmental crises, which put the party's environmental and health policies in great doubt.\n\n===Science and politics===\nThe Pakistan Muslim League (N) is credited for ordering and authorizing the country's first nuclear tests (see ''[[Chagai-I]]'' and ''[[Chagai-II]]'') amid immense international pressure. It is also responsible for establishing the [[Pakistan Antarctic Programme]] as part of its science and technology strategy. Together with their main rival, the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]], the Pakistan Muslim League (N) is also responsible for increasing [[Pakistan and its Nuclear Deterrent Program|Pakistan's nuclear deterrent]] as well as boosting the nation's [[Nuclear power in Pakistan|nuclear power]] growth, first establishing the [[Chashma Nuclear Power Plant]] expansion as part of its nuclear policy.\n\n===Foreign policy issues===\n{{Main|Pakistan's role in the War on Terror}}\nThe party has been long advocated for broader and stronger [[Foreign policy of Pakistan|relations]] with the [[Pakistan\u2013United States relations|United States]], [[China\u2013Pakistan relations|China]], the [[Pakistan\u2013United Kingdom relations|United Kingdom]], [[Pakistan\u2013European Union relations|European Union]], [[Pakistan\u2013Singapore relations|Singapore]], [[Malaysia\u2013Pakistan relations|Malaysia]], and [[Pakistan and the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation|the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]], as well as [[India\u2013Pakistan relations|India]].<ref name=\"Pakistan Muslim League-N\">{{cite web|title=National Security and Foreign Policy|url=http://pmln.org/national-security-and-foreign-policy/|publisher=PML-N Official|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911060501/http://pmln.org/national-security-and-foreign-policy/|archivedate=11 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1999, the party's government successfully signed the ''[[Lahore Declaration]]'' with India.<ref name=\"Pakistan Muslim League-N\"/>\n\nThe Pakistan Muslim League (N) remains sceptical about [[Pakistan's role in the War on Terror|the country's role in the war on terror]], although it is firmly opposed to religious extremism and terrorism in all its manifestations.<ref name=\"PMLN-Extremism and Terrorism\">{{cite web|publisher=PML-N Official|title=Extremism and Terrorism|url=http://pmln.org/extremism-and-terrorism/|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911055544/http://pmln.org/extremism-and-terrorism/|archivedate=11 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While it remains a strong supporter of the United States' financial and fiscal policies, it remains undecided about the military operations on its western frontier to curb militancy, with many PML-N intellectuals regarding the War on Terror as a campaign against Islam.<ref name=\"PMLN-Extremism and Terrorism\"/> During its previous tenure from 1997 to 1999, the PML-N government took a series of measures to control terrorist groups by establishing the [[Anti Terrorism Court of Pakistan|Anti Terrorism Courts]].<ref name=\"PMLN-Extremism and Terrorism\"/> The PML-N's leadership remains an avid supporter of [[Indian-held Kashmir]], and numerous times it had made it clear that the party will \"never compromise this long standing position on Kashmir dispute\".<ref name=\"PMLN-Extremism and Terrorism\"/>\n\n==Leaders==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"min-width:40em\"\n!colspan=5|List of [[President of Pakistan Muslim League (N)]]\n|-\n!Order!!Image!! Presidents!! Year !! Rationale\n|-\n|1||[[File:Nawaz Sharif detail, 981203-D-9880W-117.jpg|90px]] || [[Nawaz Sharif]]|| 1993\u20131999|| First term\n|-\n|2||[[File:Kalsoom Nawaz Sharif - White House - 2013 (cropped).jpg|90px]] || [[Kalsoom nawaz|Kulsoom Nawaz]] || 1999\u20132001 || First term\n|-\n|3|| [[File:Makhdoom Muhammad Javed Hashmi 01.JPG|90px]] || [[Javed Hashmi]] || 2001-2005 || First term\n|-\n|4|| [[File:Nisar Ali Khan.png|90px]] || [[Nisar Ali Khan|Chaudhry Nisar Ali]] || 2005\u20132009 || First term\n|-\n|5|| [[File:Shahbaz Sharif (cropped).jpg|90px]] || [[Shehbaz Sharif]] || 2009\u20132010 || First term\n|-\n|(3)|| [[File:Makhdoom Muhammad Javed Hashmi 01.JPG|90px]] || [[Javed Hashmi]] || 2010-2011 || Second term\n|-\n|(1)||[[File:PrimeMinisterNawazSharif.jpg|90px]] || [[Nawaz Sharif]]|| 2011\u20132017|| Second term\n|-\n|(5)|| ||[[Sardar Yaqoob|Sardar Yaqoob Khan Nasir]]|| 2017|| First term\n|-\n|(1)||[[File:PrimeMinisterNawazSharif.jpg|90px]] || [[Nawaz Sharif]]|| 2017\u20132018|| Third term\n|-\n|(5)|| [[File:Shahbaz Sharif (cropped).jpg|90px]] || [[Shehbaz Sharif]] || 2018\u2013present || Second term\n|-\n|}\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Rise to power with help from military establishment===\n[[Nawaz Sharif]]'s rise to power is attributed to funding and backing from [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] and the military establishment. Former director general of ISI [[Hamid Gul]] admitted that he formed [[Islami Jamhoori Ittehad|Islami Jamhuri Itehad]] in order to counter the power of [[Pakistan Peoples Party|the Pakistan People's Party]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/760219|title=Hamid Gul accepts responsibility for creating IJI|date=2012-10-30|newspaper=DAWN.COM|access-date=2017-01-04|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104164903/http://www.dawn.com/news/760219|archivedate=4 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Operation Clean-up===\n{{Main|Operation Clean-up}}\nNawaz Sharif, during his first tenure as prime minister of Pakistan (1990-1993), launched a [[military operation]] against his own allies in government, MQM, for allegations against [[Jinnahpur|the Jinnahpur conspiracy]]. Later, the ISPR denied any knowledge of the Jinnahpur conspiracy and separatist maps, which were highly publicized in the media prior to the operation's launch. Thousands of MQM activists were killed, its leadership arrested, and its head, [[Altaf Hussain (Pakistani politician)|Altaf Hussain]], fled to exile in the UK.\n\n===Operation 1998===\nDuring his second term as prime minister (1997-1999), Nawaz Sharif again launched an operation against MQM, who were again in alliance in Sharif's government, on accusations of assassinating [[Hakim Said|Hakeem Said]]. Due to MQM's militant activities and sectarian killings in Karachi, Nawaz Sharif was forced to end the alliance with MQM for the benefit of the nation. An elected PMLN Sindh government in alliance with MQM was dismissed and President's rule was imposed. The operation launched a new era of bloodshed in [[Karachi]] and many party leaders from MQM were arrested. [[Imran Farooq]] (MQM second in command at that time) was forced to flee Pakistan and took political asylum in the UK. Fasih Jugu, who was accused of assassination, was tortured to death by law enforcement officers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/646162-hakim-said-murder-still-shrouded-in-mystery|title=Hakim Said murder still shrouded in mystery|website=www.thenews.com.pk|access-date=2017-01-04|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104164224/https://www.thenews.com.pk/archive/print/646162-hakim-said-murder-still-shrouded-in-mystery|archivedate=4 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The operation resulted in major unrest as the PMLN government tried to nab the criminal elements ravaging the city of Karachi. This was one of the prime excuses the military conjured up for illegally ousting Nawaz Sharif's government in 1999 through martial law.\n\n===Plane hijacking===\nIn 1999, Nawaz Sharif was allegedly involved in the hijacking of a plane carrying then Chief of Army Staff Pervez Musharraf as it was about to land at [[Jinnah International Airport|Karachi airport]], and the control tower ordered the plane not to land in Pakistan but India instead. However, Musharraf and his loyalists had been planning a coup for months and some versions of the story claim that Musharraf orchestrated the coup from the plane and the military didn't allow the plane to land until Musharraf was assured that the military was in control of the airport. The military forced the courts to convict Sharif and sentence him to life imprisonment in 2000. General Musharraf had initially decided to hang Nawaz Sharif but under pressure from the President of the United States Bill Clinton and King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia, he decided not to go through with the plan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/pakistans-deposed-pm-waits-to-hear-if-he-will-be-hanged-279668.html|title=Pakistan's deposed PM waits to hear if he will be hanged|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-06-11|language=en-GB}}</ref> In 2010, The Supreme Court of Pakistan overturned Nawaz' conviction, making him eligible to run for power again.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jul/17/nawaz-sharif-hijack-conviction-overturned|title=Pakistan court quashes Sharif hijacking conviction|last=Press|first=Associated|date=2009-07-17|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2017-01-04|url-status = live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104165340/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jul/17/nawaz-sharif-hijack-conviction-overturned|archivedate=4 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Allegations of corruption===\nPMLN has been accused of corruption in revolutionary economic schemes such as the Yellow Cab Scheme, The National Debt Retirement Programme (NDRP), the Sasti Roti Scheme, and the [[Nandipur Power Project]]. The charges turned out to be nothing more than accusations by rival political parties to mislead the public. More recently, an international newspaper published [[Panama Papers|the Panama papers]], naming Sharif's sons as among people who created offshore companies. Nawaz Sharif is accused of using corruption money to grow his assets in his business ventures and [[Ittefaq Group|Ittefaq group]], though nothing presented in court so far substantiates these charges.\n\n===Panama papers case and its implications===\n\nThe Panama Papers case, was a landmark decision by the Supreme Court of Pakistan that disqualified the incumbent Prime Minister of Pakistan Nawaz Sharif from holding public office for life.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-40750671|title=Pakistan PM Sharif resigns after verdict|date=2017-07-28|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> The Supreme Court of Pakistan was petitioned by opposition politicians Imran Khan and Sheikh Rasheed, in the aftermath of the Panama Papers leak, which uncovered links between the Sharif family and eight offshore companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/11/pakistan-supreme-court-hears-panama-leaks-case-161101080340730.html|title=Pakistan: Supreme Court hears Panama leaks case|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/01/maryam-safdar-named-panama-papers-beneficiary-170123132820149.html|title=Maryam Safdar named in Panama Papers as beneficiary|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dunyanews.tv/en/Pakistan/369465-PTI-lawyer-presents-arguments-in-Panama-Papers-cas|title=PTI lawyer presents arguments in Panama Papers case - Pakistan - Dunya News|website=dunyanews.tv|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> The Court ordered for a Joint Investigation Team to be formed for the inquiry into allegations of money laundering, corruption and contradictory statements made by the Sharif family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1336384/sc-reserves-judgment-panamagate-case/|title=SC reserves judgment in Panamagate case|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2017-02-23|website=The Express Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> On 10 July 2017, JIT submitted a 275-page report <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.suchtv.pk/pakistan/general/item/56626-panama-case-jit-complete-report.html|title=Read Complete Report of Joint Investigation Team (JIT) in Panama Case|last=Desk|first=News|website=SUCH TV|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/353599441/Panama-Case-JIT-Full-Report|title=Panama Case JIT Full Report|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> to the Supreme Court of Pakistan. The report found that Sharif, his sons and his daughter Maryam Nawaz could not justify their income nor their assets, adding that Maryam Nawaz had been proved to be a beneficial owner of Nielsen and Nescoll.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.samaa.tv/news/2017/07/jit-report-recommends-filing-of-reference-against-pm-sons-in-nab/|title=JIT recommends filing of reference against PM, sons with NAB {{!}} Samaa Digital|website=Samaa TV|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> The report also showed that Maryam Nawaz had falsified evidence before the Supreme Court, proven as the Calibri font used in the document did not exist at the time when documents were said to have been created.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1344654|title=JIT report raises doubts about use of &#39;Calibri&#39; font in papers submitted by Maryam|last=Dawn.com|date=2017-07-11|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1344685|title=We asked the creator of Calibri to weigh in on the JIT debate|last=Siddiqui|first=Zain|date=2017-07-12|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> After hearing all arguments and based on evidence provided by the JIT, the Supreme Court of Pakistan announced its unanimous decision and disqualified the Prime Minister from holding public office, finding that he had been dishonest in not disclosing his employed in the Dubai-based Capital FZE company in his nomination papers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1348191|title=Nawaz Sharif steps down as PM after SC&#39;s disqualification verdict|last=Dawn.com|first=Haseeb Bhatti {{!}}|date=2017-07-28|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\nStemming from the JIT investigation, and based on NAB's investigations, the court sentenced Nawaz Sharif to 10 years of imprisonment in relation to the Avenfield Apartments case. The sentence also extended to his daughter Maryum Nawaz, and Son-in-Law Retired Captain Safdar, who were given 7 years and 1 year imprisonment respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1418482|title=Accountability court terms Sharif family \u2018monolith\u2019 in verdict|last=Iqbal|first=Nasir|date=2018-07-07|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\nIn the following election, PMLN suffered a massive blow due to these corruptions charges, with a net loss of 24.35%.<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-44961193|title=Ex-cricketer Khan leads Pakistan elections|date=2018-07-26|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.com\"/> PMLN blamed this primarily on alleged vote rigging and administrative malpractices.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pakistan-politics-pmln-analysis-idUKKBN1IC0WH|title=Blow after blow dims re-election hopes of Pakistan's ruling party|date=2018-05-11|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en}}</ref> However, Election Commission of Pakistan (ECP) outright rejected such reports and stated that the elections were conducted fair and free.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1766411/1-ecp-rejects-political-parties-claim-rigging-election-day/|title=ECP rejects political parties' claim of 'rigging' on election day|last=Tribune.com.pk|date=2018-07-26|website=The Express Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> The European Union Election Observation Mission said, that no rigging had been found during the election, and polling was termed to be \"transparent\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.theguardian.com/world/2018/jul/27/pakistan-election-imran-khan-official-results-win-coalition|title=EU piles pressure on Imran Khan after Pakistan election {{!}} Pakistan {{!}} The Guardian|website=amp.theguardian.com|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Allegations of treachery ===\nNawaz gave an interview to Dawn News on 12 May 2018 in which he said that non-state actors from Pakistan were involved in the [[2008 Mumbai attacks|Mumbai terrorist attacks]] in 2008. A spokesman for Sharif said that Indian media had twisted his statement to make it seem like he had suggested that the state of Pakistan endorsed and was directly involved in the attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/nawaz-sharif-grossly-misinterpreted-over-remarks-on-mumbai-attack-party-blames-malicious-propaganda-by-media-4468209.html|title=Nawaz Sharif 'grossly misinterpreted' over remarks on Mumbai attack: Party blames 'malicious propaganda' by media - Firstpost|website=www.firstpost.com|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref> A National Security Council meeting was called by the Pakistan Army which declared the allegations were based on lies and misconception without specifically naming Sharif.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1407628|title=NSC unanimously terms 'statement' on Mumbai attacks as 'incorrect and misleading'|last=Hussain|first=Dawn.com {{!}} Sanaullah Khan {{!}} Javed|date=2018-05-14|work=DAWN.COM|access-date=2018-06-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Pakistan|Politics|Conservatism}}\n* [[Pakistan Movement]]\n* [[Liaquat Ali Khan]]\n* [[Pakistan\u2013United States relations]]\n* [[Cold War]]\n* [[Conservatism in Pakistan|Right-wing politics in Pakistan]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{small|{{cite book|last1=Dixit|first1=J.N.|title=India-Pakistan in War and Peace|date=2002|publisher=Routledge.|location=New York, U.S.|isbn=1134407572|pages=504| ref=harv}} }}\n*{{small|{{cite book|last1=Jalal|first1=Ayesha|title=The struggle for Pakistan: A Muslim homeland and global politics|date=2014|publisher=Harvard University Press|location=Harvard, United States|isbn=0674052897|pages=440|ref=harv }} }}\n*{{small|{{cite book|last1=Akbar|first1=M.K.|title=Pakistan from Jinnah to Sharif|date=1997|publisher=Mittal Publications|location=New Delhi|isbn=8170996740|ref=harv }} }}\n*{{small|{{cite book|last1=Ahmed|first1=Akbar|title=Jinnah, Pakistan, and Islamic Identitiy: A search for Saladin|date=2005|publisher=Routledge|isbn=1134750226|ref=harv }} }}\n*{{small|{{cite book|last1=Majumdar|first1=edited by R.|title=Pakistan : Jinnah to the present day|date=1998|publisher=Anmol Publications|location=New Delhi|isbn=8174888640|edition=1st|ref=harv }} }}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Contains Urdu text}}\n{{Commons category|Pakistan Muslim League (N)}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.pmln.org/}}\n\n{{Pakistani political parties}}\n{{Pakistan topics}}\n{{Conservatism in Pakistan}}\n\n[[Category:Pakistan Muslim League (N)]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Political parties in Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "Abbasi786786", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNational Assembly elections:Added PML(N) map", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pakistan_Muslim_League_(N)"}
{"title_page": "Wang Yinglai", "text_new": "{{short description|Chinese biochemist}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Wang (surname)|Wang]]}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name=Wang Yinglai\n|native_name = \u738b\u5e94\u7750\n|image=Wang Yinglai.png\n|alt=\n|caption=Wang Yinglai at Cambridge University in 1938\n|birth_date={{birth date|1907|11|13|df=yes}}\n|birth_place=[[Kinmen]], [[Fujian]], [[Qing China]]\n|death_date={{Death date and age|2001|5|5|1907|11|13|df=yes}}\n|death_place=[[Shanghai]], China\n|fields=[[Biochemistry]]\n|known_for=Total chemical synthesis of [[insulin]] and [[tRNA]]\n|years_active=\n|alma_mater=[[University of Nanking]]<br/>[[University of Cambridge]]\n|work_institutions=[[University of Cambridge]]<br />[[Shanghai Institute of Biochemistry]]\n|doctoral_advisor = [[David Keilin]]\n|notable_students = [[Li Zaiping]], [[Xu Genjun]], [[Hong Guofan]], [[Liu Xinyuan]], [[Wang Enduo]]\n|prizes=Special Achievement Award, Miami Winter Symposium (1988)<br />[[Ho Leung Ho Lee Prize]] (1996)\n|spouse = Liu Runling\n|module = {{Chinese |child=yes |s=\u738b\u5e94\u7750 |t=\u738b\u61c9\u775e |p=W\u00e1ng Y\u012bngl\u00e0i |w=Wang Ying-lai}}\n}}\n\n'''Wang Yinglai''' ({{zh|s=\u738b\u5e94\u7750}}; 13 November 1907 \u2013 5 May 2001), also known as '''Ying-Lai Wang''', was a Chinese biochemist recognized as the first person to create synthetic [[insulin]],<ref name=\"nature\">{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=L. Ling-chi|date=2001-07-05|title=Obituary: Wang Ying-lai (1907\u20132001)|journal=Nature|volume=412|issue=6842|pages=38|doi=10.1038/35083684|pmid=11452292|issn=0028-0836}}</ref><ref name=\"utmb\">{{Cite web|url=https://scsb.utmb.edu/wyl-memorial/wangyinglai.asp|title=Wang Ying-Lai|website=Sealy Center for Structural Biology and Molecular Biophysics, University of Texas Medical Branch|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref> a major scientific breakthrough that produced a biologically active compound from inorganic chemicals.<ref name=\"utmb\" /> He was one of the first group of scientists elected to the [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]] in 1955. He founded the [[Shanghai Institute of Biochemistry]] in 1958 and served as its director until his retirement in 1984.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nWang was born in [[Kinmen|Kinmen County]] (Quemoy), [[Fujian]] Province on 13 November 1907, in the final years of the [[Qing dynasty]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.93.gov.cn/html/93gov/syfc/lyys/zgkxyys/yq/130111150650000828.html|title=\u738b\u5e94\u7750|date=2017-11-15|website=Jiusan Society|access-date=2018-06-15}}</ref> He became an orphan at the age of six when his mother died.<ref name=\"utmb\" /> His father, an [[Overseas Chinese]] merchant, had died four years before.<ref name=\":0\" /> Despite the adverse circumstances, he pursued an education throughout the 1920s and 1930s, when China was mired in wars and turmoil. He graduated from the Department of Chemistry of the [[University of Nanking]] (Jinling University) and was admitted to the graduate school of the [[University of Cambridge]] in 1938, where he studied under [[David Keilin]]. After obtaining his Ph.D. in 1941, Wang stayed to teach at Cambridge and conduct research at the [[Dunn Nutritional Laboratory]]. He transferred to the [[Molteno Institute for Research in Parasitology]] in 1944.<ref name=\"utmb\" />\n\n== Career ==\nWang returned to China at the end of World War II despite efforts by Keilin and [[Joseph Needham]] to persuade him to stay at Cambridge. Determined to help develop scientific research in China, he accepted a research professorship at the medical school of the [[National Central University]] in [[Nanjing]], and later joined the Medical Institute of [[Academia Sinica]] in 1948.<ref name=\"utmb\" />\n\nAfter the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949, Wang became deputy director of the newly established Shanghai Institute of Physiology and Biochemistry, under director [[Bei Shizhang]]. In 1955, he was among the first group of scientists to be elected to the newly established [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]]. In 1958, he established the [[Shanghai Institute of Biochemistry]] and served as its director until his retirement in 1984.<ref name=\"utmb\" /> In these capacities, he recruited many prominent Chinese scientists from abroad, including future academicians [[Cao Tianqin]], [[Chen-Lu Tsou]] (Zou Chenglu), [[Wang Debao]] and [[Niu Jingyi]].<ref name=\"zhang\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=Baoyuan|last2=Xue|first2=Pangao|last3=Wang|first3=Enduo |authorlink3=Wang Enduo |date=July 2011|title=Yinglai Wang: an admirable biochemist for his foresightedness and selflessness|url=https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1007%2Fs13238-011-1075-5.pdf|journal=Protein & Cell|volume=2|issue=7|pages=517\u2013518|doi=10.1007/s13238-011-1075-5|issn=1674-800X|pmc=4875238|pmid=21822796}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lin|first=Qi-Shui|last2=Li|first2=Bo-Liang|date=2001-02-01|title=In Memory of Professor WANG Ying-Lai.|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/11333497|journal=Acta Biochimica et Biophysica Sinica|volume=33|issue=4|pages=365\u2013367|pmid=12040406}}</ref>\n\nWang's most significant contribution was the total chemical synthesis of insulin. He started the project in 1958 with a team of scientists, who first synthesized the 20 [[amino acids]] that constitute proteins, and then used them to produce chains of insulin. His team successfully synthesized insulin in 1965, the first in the world to do so. It was a major breakthrough to produce a biologically active compound from inorganic chemicals.<ref name=\"utmb\" />\n\nMany scientists, including the [[Nobel Prize]] committee member [[Arne Tiselius]] and Physics laureate [[Chen-Ning Yang]],<ref name=\"nature\" /> believed Wang's total synthesis of insulin was worthy of a Nobel Prize.<ref name=\"matson\">{{Cite news|url=https://static.nbclearn.com/files/nbcarchives/site/pdf/5460.pdf|title=Science During the Cultural Revolution in China: The Story of Wang Ying-Lai|last=Matson|first=Boyd|authorlink=Boyd Matson|date=1987-09-27|work=NBC|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref> However, the [[Cultural Revolution]] (1966\u20131976) intervened and the Chinese Communist government considered the Nobel Prize a symbol of Western decadence. Instead, Wang was held a virtual prisoner<ref name=\"matson\" /> in a building at his institute and forced to study [[Mao Zedong thought]]. He was unable to conduct research for most of the ten years.<ref name=\"matson\" /> During an interview in 1986, Wang told ''[[The Straits Times]]'' that \"we were like the proverbial hare which took a long nap while others were not like the tortoise\".<ref name=\"nature\" />\n\nAfter the end of the Cultural Revolution, Wang and his team resumed their work and achieved the synthesis from inorganic chemicals of a [[transfer RNA]] (tRNA), another significant biological molecule, in the late 1970s.<ref name=\"utmb\" />\n\nWang established several training programs for young biochemists, many of whom later became accomplished scientists, including academicians [[Li Zaiping]], [[Xu Genjun]], [[Hong Guofan]], [[Liu Xinyuan]],<ref name=\"zhang\" /> and [[Wang Enduo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.93.gov.cn/html/93gov/syfc/lyys/zgkxyys/yy/130111112690740204.html|title=\u738b\u6069\u591a|date=2018-05-25|publisher=Jiusan Society|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\nIn 1988, [[William Joseph Whelan]], the founder of the Miami Winter Symposium for Biotechnology, created the Special Achievement Award of the symposium and presented the first award to Wang.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Whelan|first=William Joseph|date=2001-06-01|title=Appreciation of Ying-Lai Wang|journal=IUBMB Life|volume=51|issue=6|pages=335\u2013336|doi=10.1080/152165401753366078|issn=1521-6543}}</ref> In 1996, he was nominated by many scientists for the [[Ho Leung Ho Lee Prize]] for Achievement in Science and Technology. When he won the award with its prize money of one million yuan, he used it to fund a scholarship for graduate students at the Chinese Academy of Sciences.<ref name=\"zhang\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nWang met Liu Runling (\u5218\u6da6\u82d3), a student at [[Yenching University]], when he was recuperating from [[tuberculosis]] in Beijing. They married and had two sons, Wang Jiahu (\u738b\u5bb6\u69f2) and Wang Jianan (\u738b\u5bb6\u6960). Liu worked as a teacher and started a kindergarten. She suffered from [[Alzheimer's disease]] in old age and died in 1992.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.xys.org/xys/ebooks/others/science/wangyinglai.txt|title=\u5e05\u624d\u79d1\u5b66\u5bb6|last=Li|first=Hujun|date=2001-08-09|work=Nanfang Weekend|access-date=2018-06-15}}</ref>\n\nWang died in Shanghai on 5 May 2001, aged 93.<ref name=\"utmb\" /> Academician [[Xu Genjun]] eulogized Wang with a quotation from the ''[[Tao Te Ching]]'': \"The top class of virtue is like water, which benefits ten thousand objects without any demands for return.\"<ref name=\"zhang\" />\n\n==Selected publications==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Adolph | first1 = W.H. | last2 = Wang | first2 = Y.L. | year = 1934 | title = The Digestibility of Soybean Milk Compared with Cow's Milk in Vitro and in Vivo | url = | journal = Chin. J. Physiol. | volume = 8 | issue = | pages = 171\u2013178 }}\n*Yudkin J., Wang Y.L., \"Assessment of the Level of Nutrition, Urinary Excretion of Aneurin at Varying Levels of Intake, Biochem. J., 1940; 34:343\u2013352.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Harris | first1 = L.J. | last2 = Wang | first2 = Y.L. | year = 1941 | title = Vitamin Methods 3, An Improved Procedure for Estimating Vitamin B1 in Foodstuffs and Biological Materials by the Throchrome Test including Comparisons with Biological Assays | url = | journal = Biochem. J. | volume = 35 | issue = 8\u20139| pages = 1050\u20131067 | doi=10.1042/bj0351050| pmid = 16747450 | pmc = 1265604 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Harris | first1 = L.J. | last2 = Mapson | first2 = M.L. | last3 = Wang | first3 = Y.L. | year = 1942 | title = Vitamin Methods 4A Potentiometric Method for the Estimation of Vitamin C in Coloured Extracts | url = | journal = Biochem. J. | volume = 36 | issue = 1\u20132| pages = 183\u2013195 | doi=10.1042/bj0360183| pmid = 16747478 | pmc = 1265673 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Moore | first1 = T. | last2 = Wang | first2 = Y.L. | year = 1945 | title = Hypervitaminosis A | url = | journal = Biochem. J. | volume = 39 | issue = 3| pages = 222\u2013228 | doi=10.1042/bj0390222| pmid = 16747891 | pmc = 1258210 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Keilin | first1 = D. | last2 = Wang | first2 = Y.L. | year = 1945 | title = Haemoglobin from the Root Nodules of Leguminous Plants | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 155 | issue = | pages = 227\u2013233 | doi=10.1038/155227a0}}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Keilin | first1 = D. | last2 = Wang | first2 = Y.L. | year = 1946 | title = The Haemoglobin of Gastrophilus Larvae Purification and Properties | url = | journal = Biochem. J. | volume = 40 | issue = 5\u20136| pages = 855\u2013866 | doi=10.1042/bj0400855| pmid = 16748097 | pmc = 1270050 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Wang | last2 = Holliday | first2 = E.R. | display-authors = etal | year = 1946 | title = Assay of Crystalline Preparations of Aneurin by Means of the Ultraviolet Absorption Spectrum | url = | journal = Quart. J. Pharm. Pharmacol | volume = 19 | issue = | pages = 155\u2013172 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Moore | first1 = T. | last2 = Wang | first2 = Y.L. | year = 1943 | title = The Fluorescence of the Tissues in Avitaminosis E | url = | journal = Proc. Biochem. Soc., (Great Britain) | volume = 37 | issue = | page = 1 }}; ''Brit. J. Nutrition'' 1947, 1:53\u201364.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Keilin | first1 = D. | last2 = Wang | first2 = Y.L. | year = 1947 | title = The Stability of Haemoglobin and of Certain Endoery throcytic Enzymes in Vitro | url = | journal = Biochem. J. | volume = 41 | issue = 4| pages = 491\u2013500 | doi=10.1042/bj0410491| pmid = 16748201 | pmc = 1258524 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Levenbok | first1 = L. | last2 = Wang | first2 = Y.L. | year = 1948 | title = Succinic Acid in the Blood of the Larva of Gastro philus Intestinalis | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 162 | issue = 4123| pages = 731\u2013732 | doi = 10.1038/162731b0 | pmid = 18933600 | bibcode = 1948Natur.162..731L }}\n<!-- *\u6768\u5149\u573b\u3001\u738b\u5e94\u7750\uff0c\u7c73\u7c92\u4e2d\u7ef4\u751f\u7d20B1\u4e0e\u70df\u9178\u7684\u5206\u5e03\uff0c\u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\uff0c1950\uff1a99\uff5e107 \u3002-->\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Chen | first1 = S.M. | last2 = Hu | first2 = H.C. | last3 = Wang | first3 = Y.L. | year = 1950 | title = On the Nature of the \"Nicotinic Acid\" Formed by Rat Liver Slices in the Presence of Tryptophan | url = | journal = Chin. J. Physiol. | volume = 17 | issue = | pages = 325\u2013334 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Wang | first1 = Y.L. | year = 1950 | title = The Effect of Bile Acids on Succinoxidase Activity | url = | journal = Chin. J. Physiol. | volume = 17 | issue = | pages = 231\u2013242 }}\n<!--\n*\u9648\u5584\u660e\u3001\u80e1\u65ed\u521d\u3001\u738b\u5e94\u7750\uff0c\u7ef4\u751f\u7d20B6\u7f3a\u4e4f\u5bf9\u9f20\u809d\u5207\u7247\u53d8\u8272\u6c28\u9178\u4e3a\"\u70df\u9178\"\u7684 \u5f71\u54cd\uff0c\u751f\u7406\u5b66\u62a5\uff0c1953\uff0c19\uff1a55\uff5e64\u3002\n*\u9648\u5584\u660e\u3001\u738b\u5e94\u7750\uff0c\u5e72\u7cae\u8102\u80aa\u9632\u6c27\u5316\uff0c\u8425\u517b\u5b66\u62a5\uff0c1953\uff0c3\uff0c(1)\u3002\n*\u5f6d\u52a0\u6728\u3001\u738b\u5e94\u7750\uff0c\u9ec4\u8c46\u82bd\u690d\u9178\u9176\u7684\u7814\u7a76\uff0c\u4e2d\u56fd\u751f\u7406\u5b66\u62a5\uff0c1954\uff0c19\uff1a247\uff5e269 \u3002\n-->\n*Wang J.Y., Tsou C.L., Wang Y.L., Studies on Succinic Dehydrogenase Isolation, Purification and Properties, Brussels, 3rd Int. Congress of Biochemistry, 1955 Scientia Sinica, 1956, 5:96\u201390.\n<!--\n*\u6797\u82e5\u7ff0\u3001\u738b\u5e94\u7750\uff0c\u7ef4\u751f\u7d20B6\u4e0e\u8272\u6