{"title_page": "Offset (rapper)", "text_new": "{{short description|American rapper}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2017}}{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Offset\n| image              = Offset Veld festival 2017.jpg\n| caption            = Offset performing in 2017\n| birth_name         = Kiari Kendrell Cephus \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1991|12|14}} \n| birth_place        = [[Lawrenceville, Georgia]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* Songwriter\n* Actor\n}}\n| years_active       = 2008\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Cardi B]]|2017}}\n| children           = 100000\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed            = yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Trap music (hip hop)|trap]]\n}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|keyboards}}\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Quality Control Music|Quality Control]]\n* [[Motown]]\n* [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n*[[Migos]]\n*[[21 Savage]]\n*[[Cardi B]]\n*[[Travis Scott]]\n*[[DaBaby]]\n*[[Metro Boomin]]\n*[[Stunna 4 Vegas]]\n*[[Quavo]]\n*[[Young Thug]]}}}}\n| website            = {{URL|https://www.yungrichnation.com/}}\n}}\n'''Kiari Kendrell Cephus''' (born December 14, 1991), known professionally as '''Offset''', is an American rapper and songwriter. He is a member of the [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[trap music (hip hop)|trap]] music trio [[Migos]], alongside his cousin [[Quavo]] and his cousin once-removed [[Takeoff (rapper)|Takeoff]]. He is also an investor in [[esports]] organization [[FaZe Clan]].\n\n==Career==\nThe members of [[Migos]] were raised middle-class in suburban Gwinnett County, Georgia. In 2008, Offset formed Migos with [[Quavo]] and [[Takeoff (rapper)|Takeoff]]. Offset is Quavo's cousin, and Quavo is Takeoff's uncle.<ref name=\"RollingStone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/migos-young-rich-and-outrunning-trouble-20150624|title=Migos: Young, Rich and Outrunning Trouble|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=June 24, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> The three grew up together in [[Gwinnett County]], a mostly suburban area near [[Atlanta]].<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/>\n\nMigos initially gained recognition following the release of their 2013 single \"[[Versace (song)|Versace]]\".<ref name=\"RollingStone\" /> In 2015, the trio released their debut studio album ''[[Yung Rich Nation]]''.<ref name=\"RollingStone\" /> In 2017, their single \"[[Bad and Boujee]]\" became an [[Internet meme|Internet phenomenon]], spawning many memes with the lyrics \"rain drop, drop top\", which were performed by Offset.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/12/migos-bad-and-boujee-memes/|title=Migos\u2019 \"Bad and Boujee\" Gets Turned Into Memes|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|date=December 28, 2016|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> The song peaked at number one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7648006/hot-100-migos-bad-and-boujee-lil-uzi-vert-number-one|title=Migos' 'Bad and Boujee,' Featuring Lil Uzi Vert, Tops Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 9, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> with many critics believing Offset commanded{{clarify|date=August 2018}} the track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/in-depth/2016/12/best-songs-2016/|title=Best Songs of 2016|work=Pigeons & Planes|date=December 19, 2016|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/1918179/the-brain-conquering-majesty-of-migos-bad-boujee/franchises/status-aint-hood/|title=The Brain-Conquering Majesty Of Migos\u2019 \"Bad & Boujee\"|work=[[Stereogum]]|date=January 4, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, the trio released their second studio album, ''[[Culture (Migos album)|Culture]]'', which debuted at number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.42263/title.migos-scores-first-1-album-with-culture|title=Migos Scores First #1 Album With \"Culture\"|work=[[HipHopDX]]|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to Migos, Offset has released solo music and collaborated with numerous artists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/05/migos-no-solo-projects/|title=Migos Have No Plans to Drop Solo Projects|work=XXL|date=May 24, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, he was featured on [[Metro Boomin]]'s single \"[[No Complaints (song)|No Complaints]]\" alongside [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], which peaked at number 71 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100,<ref name=\"NC\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/no-complaints-feat-offset-drake/id1251736621|title=No Complaints (feat. Offset & Drake) - Single by Metro Boomin|work=iTunes|accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref> and in September he joined [[Macklemore]] on the song \"Willy Wonka\", from the album ''Gemini''.<ref name=\"Gemini\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/gemini/1272352884|title=Gemini by Macklemore on Apple Music|work=iTunes|date=September 22, 2017|accessdate=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Offset would eventually release a collaborative studio album with rapper [[21 Savage]] and record producer [[Metro Boomin]] titled, ''[[Without Warning (21 Savage, Offset and Metro Boomin album)|Without Warning]]''.<ref name=\"WW\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/offset-21-savage-and-metro-boomin-dropping-without-warning-album-tonight-news.39000.html|title=Offset, 21 Savage & Metro Boomin' Dropping \"Without Warning\" Album Tonight|publisher=HotNewHipHop|date=October 30, 2017|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> The album was released on October 31, 2017 and debuted at number 4 on the US ''Billboard'' 200 chart.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/offset/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Offset - Chart History: Billboard 200|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 2, 2018}}</ref> It spawned the hit song \"[[Ric Flair Drip]]\", Offset's first solo platinum single, and highest charting US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 entry to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/offset-earns-first-solo-platinum-single-with-ric-flair-drip-news.43302.html|title=Offset Earns First Solo Platinum Single with \"Ric Flair Drip\"|website=HotNewHipHop}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/offset|title=Offset Chart History|website=Billboard}}</ref> On February 22, 2019, he released his first solo album ''[[Father of 4]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/02/offset-album-release-date/|title=Offset Announces Solo Album Release Date|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=February 10, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref> The album featured the single, \"[[Clout (Offset song)|Clout]]\", with [[Cardi B]], peaking in the top 40 of the Hot 100 at number 39.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/offset/chart-history|title=Offset|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\nIn 2016, Offset (including Migos) appeared in an episode of [[Donald Glover]]'s series ''[[Atlanta (TV series)|Atlanta]]''.  The episode aired on September 13, 2016 under the title \"Go For Broke\".<ref name=\"Atlanta\" /> He has also starred in campaigns for the fashion designers [[Gosha Rubchinskiy]], Bryce Barnes, and Lavati.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2016/9/migos-offset-gosha-rubchinskiy-editorial|title=Migos's Offset Flaunts His Ink and Style in 2016 Fall/Winter Gosha Rubchinskiy Editorial|work=Hypebeast|date=September 9, 2016|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2016/12/offset-bryce-barnes-2016-fall-winter-editorial|title=Migos' Offset Features in Bryce Barnes' 2016 Fall/Winter Editorial|work=Hypebeast|date=December 20, 2016|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2017/06/05/offset-face-footwear-brand-lavatis-second-footwear-campaign/|title=Offset Is The Face Of Footwear Brand Lavati's Second Footwear Campaign|work=[[The Source]]|date=June 5, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Offset made his debut on [[Sean Evans (interviewer)|Sean Evan]]'s [[YouTube]] series ''[[Hot Ones]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=ViralStat {{!}} Offset Screams Like Ric Flair While Eating Spicy Wings Hot Ones [Video Statistics]|url=https://viralstat.com/yt/E9o_ifDQWLE|language=en|access-date=2019-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, it was announced that Offset invested in [[esports]] organization [[FaZe Clan]]. Commenting on the investment he said \"I love gaming and esports is the future\u201d said Cephus in a release, \u201cThese two facts make it only right that I be a part of the biggest esports organization with some of the best players in the world.\" He appeared in two FaZe Clan videos on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://esportsobserver.com/offset-investment-faze-clan/|title=American Rapper Offset Makes Investment in FaZe Clan|website=esportsobserver.com|accessdate=August 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=FaZe Clan: Who Can Punch the Hardest Challenge ft. Offset|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xZcW-mDsbRE|language=en|accessdate=September 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=CRAZY WHATS IN THE BOX CHALLENGE ft. OFFSET|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-bnYcZfYngw|language=en|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn January 2018, Offset was criticized for rapping a line that includes the lyrics \"I cannot vibe with queers\" in his feature on [[YFN Lucci]]'s Boss Life.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boss Life (feat. Offset) - Single by YFN Lucci |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/boss-life-feat-offset-single/1324122692 |website=Apple Music |accessdate=January 23, 2019 |date=December 15, 2017}}</ref> After the lyric was understood as homophobic he apologized saying he did not intend for his use of the term \"queer\" to be directed at the [[LGBT]] community. His wife, Cardi B, said that Offset did not know the term \"queer\" had a homophobic history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8095276/cardi-b-defend-migos-offset-over-homophobic-lyric-controversy|title=Watch Cardi B Defend Migos' Offset Over Homophobic Lyric Controversy|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref> He has mentioned that he assumed the lyric was using the definition of \"queer\" that is defined as eccentric and odd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/01/offset-apologizes-homophobic-lyrics/|title=Offset Apologizes for Homophobic Lyric - XXL|website=XXL Mag|language=en|access-date=2018-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2017, Offset started dating American rapper [[Cardi B]]. On October 27, 2017, he proposed to her at a live performance at Power 99's Powerhouse in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. On April 7, 2018, Cardi B revealed on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' that the two were expecting their first child.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8297568/cardi-b-pregnant-snl |title=Cardi B Reveals Pregnancy in 'SNL' Performance |last=DiMeglio |first=Mary J. |date=April 8, 2018 |work=Billboard |access-date=April 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOffset is the father of four children: sons Jordan and Kody and daughter Kalea from early relationships,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/11/offset-admits-another-son-court-documents/|title=Offset Admits He Has Another Son in Court Documents  - XXL|website=XXL Mag}}</ref> and a daughter with Cardi B, named Kulture Kiari Cephus, born July 10, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/amp/Entertainment/wireStory/cardi-announces-birth-daughter-instagram-56511854|title=Cardi B announces birth of daughter on Instagram|first=ABC|last=News|publisher=|accessdate=July 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713233411/https://abcnews.go.com/amp/Entertainment/wireStory/cardi-announces-birth-daughter-instagram-56511854|archive-date=July 13, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Cardi B]] and Offset married privately on September 20, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8021967/cardi-b-offset-relationship-timeline|title=Cardi B and Offset's Relationship: A Timeline|website=Billboard}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8462548/cardi-b-offset-married |title=Cardi B Confirms Secret Marriage to Offset: 'There Are Some Moments I Want to Keep for Myself' |last=Whittum |first=Connor |date=June 25, 2018 |work=Billboard |accessdate=June 25, 2018}}</ref> On December 5, 2018 Cardi B announced on [[Instagram]] that she and Offset had broken up. This is after Cephus allegedly cheated on Cardi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/music/cardi-b-offset-split/|title=Cardi B Says She and Husband Offset Are Not Together Anymore: 'I Guess We Fell Out of Love'|last1=Merrett|first1=Robyn|last2=Sands|first2=Nicole|website=People|publisher=People|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref> They later reconciled.\n\n===Legal issues===\n[[File:Kiari Kendrell Cephus.jpg|thumb|Offset's mugshot following his charges for battery and inciting a riot in May 2015]]\nWhen Migos first rose to prominence in 2013, Offset was incarcerated in Georgia's DeKalb County jail for violating his probation that he had received due to prior felony convictions for burglary and theft.<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/><ref name=gsu>[http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2015/04/migos-denied-bond-after-georgia-southern-university-arrest/ Offset of the Migos Denied Bond After Georgia Southern University Arrest]. ''XXL''.</ref>\n\nOn April 18, 2015, authorities stopped a Migos concert at [[Georgia Southern University]] and arrested all three members of the group, as well as several members of their entourage. Offset was denied bond and was charged with possession of an unspecified Schedule II narcotic, possession of marijuana, possession of a firearm in a school safety zone and possession of a firearm during the commission of a crime.<ref name=gsu/>\n\nOn May 2, 2015, Offset, while in custody, was charged with battery and inciting a riot within a penal facility after attacking another inmate, causing severe injury.<ref name=\"S'Boro Herald 4\">{{cite web|last1=Saxon|first1=Holli|title=Migos rapper charged in Bulloch County Jail fight|url=http://www.statesboroherald.com/section/1/article/67522/|publisher=Statesboro Herald|access-date=May 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518065401/http://www.statesboroherald.com/section/1/article/67522/|archive-date=May 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In a bond hearing before Bulloch County Superior Court Judge John R. Turner on May 8, 2015, Offset was formally denied bond based on his prior criminal record as well as the jail fight. During the hearing, two members of Migos' entourage were also denied bonds while four others were granted bonds and were barred from returning to Bulloch County as a condition of their release. Judge Turner directed the four who were released not to make contact with anyone involved in the case. Offset's attorney argued that the rap trio were [[racial profiling|unfairly profiled by law enforcement]] and that officers had failed to prove ownership of the firearms and illicit drugs found within the two vans. The prosecution responded that law enforcement were present at the concert for the safety of the students and public at-large due to Migos' history of violence. Upon hearing the decision, Offset shouted profanities as he was escorted out of the courtroom.<ref name=\"S'boro Herald 5\">{{cite web|last1=Saxon|first1=Holli|title=UPDATE: Bond denial angers Migos rapper|url=https://www.statesboroherald.com/local/update-bond-denial-angers-migos-rapper/|publisher=Statesboro Herald|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter eight months in custody, Offset was released on December 4, 2015, after accepting an [[Alford plea]] deal. The deal dropped the gun, drug, and gang-related charges in exchange for pleading guilty to inciting a riot within a penal facility, paying a $1,000 fine, serving five years probation, and being banished from [[Bulloch County, Georgia|Bulloch]], [[Effingham County, Georgia|Effingham]], [[Jenkins County, Georgia|Jenkins]], and [[Screven County, Georgia|Screven]] Counties.<ref name=\"WSB-TV Plea\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wsbtv.com/news/news/local/plea-deals-keep-rap-group-migos-out-jail/npchC/|title=Plea deals keep rap group Migos out of jail|last=|first=|date=December 4, 2015|website=WSB-TV|publisher=[[Cox Media Group]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206092725/https://www.wsbtv.com/news/news/local/plea-deals-keep-rap-group-migos-out-jail/npchC/|archive-date=December 6, 2015|access-date=January 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2016, Offset was arrested for driving with a suspended license but was released the next day without having charges filed.<ref name = \"2016 arrest\">{{cite web|last=Legaspi|first=Althea|date=March 17, 2016|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/migos-offset-arrested-for-suspended-license-20160317|title=Migos' Offset Arrested for Suspended License|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=July 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, on April 5, 2018, Migos' tour bus was pulled over on a traffic violation in North Carolina. Officers searched their tour bus and found 420 grams of marijuana, 26 ounces of codeine and xanax. The group members were not arrested, Offset was not in attendance, but members of their entourage were.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8293423/migos-entourage-arrested-drugs-tour-bus|title=Three Members of Migos' Entourage Arrested After Police Find Drugs on Tour Bus|last=|first=|date=April 6, 2018|website=Billboard|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2019, Offset faced a felony charge for possession of three handguns and the possession of drugs from a previous arrest in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/cardi-b-husband-rapper-offset-felony-gun-charge-georgia-traffic-stop-arrest-report|title=Cardi B husband Offset hit with felony gun charge in Georgia traffic stop arrest: report|last=|first=|date=April 23, 2019|website=Fox News|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=April 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/music/offset-charged-with-felony-possession-of-firearm/|title=Cardi B's Husband Offset Charged with Felony Possession of a Firearm Stemming from His 2018 Arrest|last=Tracy|first=Brianne|date=April 23, 2019|website=People|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=April 23, 2019}}</ref>  The news of the charges made their way to several social media platforms, including TheShadeRoom, and resulted in his wife, [[Cardi B]], expressing her anger and how they fail to show the artist and his cohorts positive accomplishments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/cardi-b-drags-the-shade-room-for-posting-negatively-in-new-rant-news.78102.html|title=Cardi B Drags The Shade Room For Posting Negatively In New Rant|last=Ciss\u00e9|first=Aida|date=April 23, 2019|website=Hot New Hip Hop|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=April 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Offset discography}}\n{{See also|Migos discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n\n* ''[[Father of 4]]'' (2019)\n\n===Collaborative albums===\n\n* ''[[Without Warning (21 Savage, Offset and Metro Boomin album)|Without Warning]]'' {{small|(with [[21 Savage]] and [[Metro Boomin]])}} (2017)\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Television series\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n|| 2016 || ''[[Atlanta (TV series)|Atlanta]]''<ref name=\"Atlanta\">{{cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2016/09/15/quavo-steals-the-show-on-donald-glovers-atlanta/|title=Quavo Steals The Show On Donald Glover's 'Atlanta'|work=The Source|date=September 15, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> || Himself || Episode: \"Go for Broke\"\n|-\n|| 2020 || ''[[NCIS: Los Angeles (TV series)|NCIS: Los Angeles]]''<ref name=\"NCIS: Los Angeles\">{{cite web|last=Elassar |first=Alaa |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/29/entertainment/offset-ncis-los-angeles-trnd/index.html |title=Offset is making his acting debut on 'NCIS: Los Angeles' |website=Cnn.com |date=2020-02-29 |accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref> || Kadri Kashan Khan || Episode: \"Alysiyadun\"\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 100%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Award\n! scope=\"col\" | Year{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Indicates the year of ceremony. Each year is linked to the article about the awards held that year, wherever possible.}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Recipient(s) and nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[BET|BET Social Awards]]\n| 2018\n| [[Cardi B]] & Offset\n| Baewatch\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bet.com/shows/social-awards/2018/nominees/baewatch.html |title=BET Social Awards 2018 Baewatch Nominees|website=BET|access-date=August 21, 2019}} </ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Grammy Awards]]\n| [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards|2020]]\n| \"[[Clout (Offset song)|Clout]]\" {{small|(featuring [[Cardi B]])}}\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Performance|Best Rap Performance]]\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/2020-grammy-awards-complete-nominees-list |title=2020 GRAMMY Awards: Complete Nominees List|date=November 20, 2019|website=Grammy.com|access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.yungrichnation.com/}}\n\n{{Offset (rapper)}}\n{{Migos}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Offset}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lawrenceville, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Southern hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Quality Control artists]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:African-American songwriters]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Migos members]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:FaZe Clan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American rapper}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2017}}{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Offset\n| image              = Offset Veld festival 2017.jpg\n| caption            = Offset performing in 2017\n| birth_name         = Kiari Kendrell Cephus \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1991|12|14}} \n| birth_place        = [[Lawrenceville, Georgia]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* Songwriter\n* Actor\n}}\n| years_active       = 2008\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Cardi B]]|2017}}\n| children           = 4\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed            = yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Trap music (hip hop)|trap]]\n}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|keyboards}}\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Quality Control Music|Quality Control]]\n* [[Motown]]\n* [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n*[[Migos]]\n*[[21 Savage]]\n*[[Cardi B]]\n*[[Travis Scott]]\n*[[DaBaby]]\n*[[Metro Boomin]]\n*[[Stunna 4 Vegas]]\n*[[Quavo]]\n*[[Young Thug]]}}}}\n| website            = {{URL|https://www.yungrichnation.com/}}\n}}\n'''Kiari Kendrell Cephus''' (born December 14, 1991), known professionally as '''Offset''', is an American rapper and songwriter. He is a member of the [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[trap music (hip hop)|trap]] music trio [[Migos]], alongside his cousin [[Quavo]] and his cousin once-removed [[Takeoff (rapper)|Takeoff]]. He is also an investor in [[esports]] organization [[FaZe Clan]].\n\n==Career==\nThe members of [[Migos]] were raised middle-class in suburban Gwinnett County, Georgia. In 2008, Offset formed Migos with [[Quavo]] and [[Takeoff (rapper)|Takeoff]]. Offset is Quavo's cousin, and Quavo is Takeoff's uncle.<ref name=\"RollingStone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/migos-young-rich-and-outrunning-trouble-20150624|title=Migos: Young, Rich and Outrunning Trouble|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=June 24, 2015|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> The three grew up together in [[Gwinnett County]], a mostly suburban area near [[Atlanta]].<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/>\n\nMigos initially gained recognition following the release of their 2013 single \"[[Versace (song)|Versace]]\".<ref name=\"RollingStone\" /> In 2015, the trio released their debut studio album ''[[Yung Rich Nation]]''.<ref name=\"RollingStone\" /> In 2017, their single \"[[Bad and Boujee]]\" became an [[Internet meme|Internet phenomenon]], spawning many memes with the lyrics \"rain drop, drop top\", which were performed by Offset.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/12/migos-bad-and-boujee-memes/|title=Migos\u2019 \"Bad and Boujee\" Gets Turned Into Memes|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|date=December 28, 2016|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> The song peaked at number one on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7648006/hot-100-migos-bad-and-boujee-lil-uzi-vert-number-one|title=Migos' 'Bad and Boujee,' Featuring Lil Uzi Vert, Tops Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 9, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> with many critics believing Offset commanded{{clarify|date=August 2018}} the track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pigeonsandplanes.com/in-depth/2016/12/best-songs-2016/|title=Best Songs of 2016|work=Pigeons & Planes|date=December 19, 2016|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/1918179/the-brain-conquering-majesty-of-migos-bad-boujee/franchises/status-aint-hood/|title=The Brain-Conquering Majesty Of Migos\u2019 \"Bad & Boujee\"|work=[[Stereogum]]|date=January 4, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, the trio released their second studio album, ''[[Culture (Migos album)|Culture]]'', which debuted at number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.42263/title.migos-scores-first-1-album-with-culture|title=Migos Scores First #1 Album With \"Culture\"|work=[[HipHopDX]]|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to Migos, Offset has released solo music and collaborated with numerous artists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/05/migos-no-solo-projects/|title=Migos Have No Plans to Drop Solo Projects|work=XXL|date=May 24, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, he was featured on [[Metro Boomin]]'s single \"[[No Complaints (song)|No Complaints]]\" alongside [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], which peaked at number 71 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100,<ref name=\"NC\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/no-complaints-feat-offset-drake/id1251736621|title=No Complaints (feat. Offset & Drake) - Single by Metro Boomin|work=iTunes|accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref> and in September he joined [[Macklemore]] on the song \"Willy Wonka\", from the album ''Gemini''.<ref name=\"Gemini\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/gemini/1272352884|title=Gemini by Macklemore on Apple Music|work=iTunes|date=September 22, 2017|accessdate=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Offset would eventually release a collaborative studio album with rapper [[21 Savage]] and record producer [[Metro Boomin]] titled, ''[[Without Warning (21 Savage, Offset and Metro Boomin album)|Without Warning]]''.<ref name=\"WW\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/offset-21-savage-and-metro-boomin-dropping-without-warning-album-tonight-news.39000.html|title=Offset, 21 Savage & Metro Boomin' Dropping \"Without Warning\" Album Tonight|publisher=HotNewHipHop|date=October 30, 2017|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> The album was released on October 31, 2017 and debuted at number 4 on the US ''Billboard'' 200 chart.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/offset/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Offset - Chart History: Billboard 200|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 2, 2018}}</ref> It spawned the hit song \"[[Ric Flair Drip]]\", Offset's first solo platinum single, and highest charting US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 entry to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/offset-earns-first-solo-platinum-single-with-ric-flair-drip-news.43302.html|title=Offset Earns First Solo Platinum Single with \"Ric Flair Drip\"|website=HotNewHipHop}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/offset|title=Offset Chart History|website=Billboard}}</ref> On February 22, 2019, he released his first solo album ''[[Father of 4]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/02/offset-album-release-date/|title=Offset Announces Solo Album Release Date|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=February 10, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref> The album featured the single, \"[[Clout (Offset song)|Clout]]\", with [[Cardi B]], peaking in the top 40 of the Hot 100 at number 39.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/offset/chart-history|title=Offset|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\nIn 2016, Offset (including Migos) appeared in an episode of [[Donald Glover]]'s series ''[[Atlanta (TV series)|Atlanta]]''.  The episode aired on September 13, 2016 under the title \"Go For Broke\".<ref name=\"Atlanta\" /> He has also starred in campaigns for the fashion designers [[Gosha Rubchinskiy]], Bryce Barnes, and Lavati.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2016/9/migos-offset-gosha-rubchinskiy-editorial|title=Migos's Offset Flaunts His Ink and Style in 2016 Fall/Winter Gosha Rubchinskiy Editorial|work=Hypebeast|date=September 9, 2016|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2016/12/offset-bryce-barnes-2016-fall-winter-editorial|title=Migos' Offset Features in Bryce Barnes' 2016 Fall/Winter Editorial|work=Hypebeast|date=December 20, 2016|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2017/06/05/offset-face-footwear-brand-lavatis-second-footwear-campaign/|title=Offset Is The Face Of Footwear Brand Lavati's Second Footwear Campaign|work=[[The Source]]|date=June 5, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Offset made his debut on [[Sean Evans (interviewer)|Sean Evan]]'s [[YouTube]] series ''[[Hot Ones]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=ViralStat {{!}} Offset Screams Like Ric Flair While Eating Spicy Wings Hot Ones [Video Statistics]|url=https://viralstat.com/yt/E9o_ifDQWLE|language=en|access-date=2019-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, it was announced that Offset invested in [[esports]] organization [[FaZe Clan]]. Commenting on the investment he said \"I love gaming and esports is the future\u201d said Cephus in a release, \u201cThese two facts make it only right that I be a part of the biggest esports organization with some of the best players in the world.\" He appeared in two FaZe Clan videos on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://esportsobserver.com/offset-investment-faze-clan/|title=American Rapper Offset Makes Investment in FaZe Clan|website=esportsobserver.com|accessdate=August 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=FaZe Clan: Who Can Punch the Hardest Challenge ft. Offset|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xZcW-mDsbRE|language=en|accessdate=September 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=CRAZY WHATS IN THE BOX CHALLENGE ft. OFFSET|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-bnYcZfYngw|language=en|accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn January 2018, Offset was criticized for rapping a line that includes the lyrics \"I cannot vibe with queers\" in his feature on [[YFN Lucci]]'s Boss Life.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boss Life (feat. Offset) - Single by YFN Lucci |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/boss-life-feat-offset-single/1324122692 |website=Apple Music |accessdate=January 23, 2019 |date=December 15, 2017}}</ref> After the lyric was understood as homophobic he apologized saying he did not intend for his use of the term \"queer\" to be directed at the [[LGBT]] community. His wife, Cardi B, said that Offset did not know the term \"queer\" had a homophobic history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8095276/cardi-b-defend-migos-offset-over-homophobic-lyric-controversy|title=Watch Cardi B Defend Migos' Offset Over Homophobic Lyric Controversy|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-03-07}}</ref> He has mentioned that he assumed the lyric was using the definition of \"queer\" that is defined as eccentric and odd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/01/offset-apologizes-homophobic-lyrics/|title=Offset Apologizes for Homophobic Lyric - XXL|website=XXL Mag|language=en|access-date=2018-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2017, Offset started dating American rapper [[Cardi B]]. On October 27, 2017, he proposed to her at a live performance at Power 99's Powerhouse in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. On April 7, 2018, Cardi B revealed on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' that the two were expecting their first child.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8297568/cardi-b-pregnant-snl |title=Cardi B Reveals Pregnancy in 'SNL' Performance |last=DiMeglio |first=Mary J. |date=April 8, 2018 |work=Billboard |access-date=April 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOffset is the father of four children: sons Jordan and Kody and daughter Kalea from early relationships,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/11/offset-admits-another-son-court-documents/|title=Offset Admits He Has Another Son in Court Documents  - XXL|website=XXL Mag}}</ref> and a daughter with Cardi B, named Kulture Kiari Cephus, born July 10, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/amp/Entertainment/wireStory/cardi-announces-birth-daughter-instagram-56511854|title=Cardi B announces birth of daughter on Instagram|first=ABC|last=News|publisher=|accessdate=July 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713233411/https://abcnews.go.com/amp/Entertainment/wireStory/cardi-announces-birth-daughter-instagram-56511854|archive-date=July 13, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Cardi B]] and Offset married privately on September 20, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8021967/cardi-b-offset-relationship-timeline|title=Cardi B and Offset's Relationship: A Timeline|website=Billboard}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8462548/cardi-b-offset-married |title=Cardi B Confirms Secret Marriage to Offset: 'There Are Some Moments I Want to Keep for Myself' |last=Whittum |first=Connor |date=June 25, 2018 |work=Billboard |accessdate=June 25, 2018}}</ref> On December 5, 2018 Cardi B announced on [[Instagram]] that she and Offset had broken up. This is after Cephus allegedly cheated on Cardi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/music/cardi-b-offset-split/|title=Cardi B Says She and Husband Offset Are Not Together Anymore: 'I Guess We Fell Out of Love'|last1=Merrett|first1=Robyn|last2=Sands|first2=Nicole|website=People|publisher=People|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref> They later reconciled.\n\n===Legal issues===\n[[File:Kiari Kendrell Cephus.jpg|thumb|Offset's mugshot following his charges for battery and inciting a riot in May 2015]]\nWhen Migos first rose to prominence in 2013, Offset was incarcerated in Georgia's DeKalb County jail for violating his probation that he had received due to prior felony convictions for burglary and theft.<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/><ref name=gsu>[http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2015/04/migos-denied-bond-after-georgia-southern-university-arrest/ Offset of the Migos Denied Bond After Georgia Southern University Arrest]. ''XXL''.</ref>\n\nOn April 18, 2015, authorities stopped a Migos concert at [[Georgia Southern University]] and arrested all three members of the group, as well as several members of their entourage. Offset was denied bond and was charged with possession of an unspecified Schedule II narcotic, possession of marijuana, possession of a firearm in a school safety zone and possession of a firearm during the commission of a crime.<ref name=gsu/>\n\nOn May 2, 2015, Offset, while in custody, was charged with battery and inciting a riot within a penal facility after attacking another inmate, causing severe injury.<ref name=\"S'Boro Herald 4\">{{cite web|last1=Saxon|first1=Holli|title=Migos rapper charged in Bulloch County Jail fight|url=http://www.statesboroherald.com/section/1/article/67522/|publisher=Statesboro Herald|access-date=May 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518065401/http://www.statesboroherald.com/section/1/article/67522/|archive-date=May 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In a bond hearing before Bulloch County Superior Court Judge John R. Turner on May 8, 2015, Offset was formally denied bond based on his prior criminal record as well as the jail fight. During the hearing, two members of Migos' entourage were also denied bonds while four others were granted bonds and were barred from returning to Bulloch County as a condition of their release. Judge Turner directed the four who were released not to make contact with anyone involved in the case. Offset's attorney argued that the rap trio were [[racial profiling|unfairly profiled by law enforcement]] and that officers had failed to prove ownership of the firearms and illicit drugs found within the two vans. The prosecution responded that law enforcement were present at the concert for the safety of the students and public at-large due to Migos' history of violence. Upon hearing the decision, Offset shouted profanities as he was escorted out of the courtroom.<ref name=\"S'boro Herald 5\">{{cite web|last1=Saxon|first1=Holli|title=UPDATE: Bond denial angers Migos rapper|url=https://www.statesboroherald.com/local/update-bond-denial-angers-migos-rapper/|publisher=Statesboro Herald|access-date=February 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter eight months in custody, Offset was released on December 4, 2015, after accepting an [[Alford plea]] deal. The deal dropped the gun, drug, and gang-related charges in exchange for pleading guilty to inciting a riot within a penal facility, paying a $1,000 fine, serving five years probation, and being banished from [[Bulloch County, Georgia|Bulloch]], [[Effingham County, Georgia|Effingham]], [[Jenkins County, Georgia|Jenkins]], and [[Screven County, Georgia|Screven]] Counties.<ref name=\"WSB-TV Plea\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wsbtv.com/news/news/local/plea-deals-keep-rap-group-migos-out-jail/npchC/|title=Plea deals keep rap group Migos out of jail|last=|first=|date=December 4, 2015|website=WSB-TV|publisher=[[Cox Media Group]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206092725/https://www.wsbtv.com/news/news/local/plea-deals-keep-rap-group-migos-out-jail/npchC/|archive-date=December 6, 2015|access-date=January 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2016, Offset was arrested for driving with a suspended license but was released the next day without having charges filed.<ref name = \"2016 arrest\">{{cite web|last=Legaspi|first=Althea|date=March 17, 2016|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/migos-offset-arrested-for-suspended-license-20160317|title=Migos' Offset Arrested for Suspended License|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=July 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, on April 5, 2018, Migos' tour bus was pulled over on a traffic violation in North Carolina. Officers searched their tour bus and found 420 grams of marijuana, 26 ounces of codeine and xanax. The group members were not arrested, Offset was not in attendance, but members of their entourage were.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8293423/migos-entourage-arrested-drugs-tour-bus|title=Three Members of Migos' Entourage Arrested After Police Find Drugs on Tour Bus|last=|first=|date=April 6, 2018|website=Billboard|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2019, Offset faced a felony charge for possession of three handguns and the possession of drugs from a previous arrest in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/cardi-b-husband-rapper-offset-felony-gun-charge-georgia-traffic-stop-arrest-report|title=Cardi B husband Offset hit with felony gun charge in Georgia traffic stop arrest: report|last=|first=|date=April 23, 2019|website=Fox News|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=April 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/music/offset-charged-with-felony-possession-of-firearm/|title=Cardi B's Husband Offset Charged with Felony Possession of a Firearm Stemming from His 2018 Arrest|last=Tracy|first=Brianne|date=April 23, 2019|website=People|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=April 23, 2019}}</ref>  The news of the charges made their way to several social media platforms, including TheShadeRoom, and resulted in his wife, [[Cardi B]], expressing her anger and how they fail to show the artist and his cohorts positive accomplishments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/cardi-b-drags-the-shade-room-for-posting-negatively-in-new-rant-news.78102.html|title=Cardi B Drags The Shade Room For Posting Negatively In New Rant|last=Ciss\u00e9|first=Aida|date=April 23, 2019|website=Hot New Hip Hop|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=April 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Offset discography}}\n{{See also|Migos discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n\n* ''[[Father of 4]]'' (2019)\n\n===Collaborative albums===\n\n* ''[[Without Warning (21 Savage, Offset and Metro Boomin album)|Without Warning]]'' {{small|(with [[21 Savage]] and [[Metro Boomin]])}} (2017)\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Television series\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n|| 2016 || ''[[Atlanta (TV series)|Atlanta]]''<ref name=\"Atlanta\">{{cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2016/09/15/quavo-steals-the-show-on-donald-glovers-atlanta/|title=Quavo Steals The Show On Donald Glover's 'Atlanta'|work=The Source|date=September 15, 2017|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> || Himself || Episode: \"Go for Broke\"\n|-\n|| 2020 || ''[[NCIS: Los Angeles (TV series)|NCIS: Los Angeles]]''<ref name=\"NCIS: Los Angeles\">{{cite web|last=Elassar |first=Alaa |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/29/entertainment/offset-ncis-los-angeles-trnd/index.html |title=Offset is making his acting debut on 'NCIS: Los Angeles' |website=Cnn.com |date=2020-02-29 |accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref> || Kadri Kashan Khan || Episode: \"Alysiyadun\"\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 100%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Award\n! scope=\"col\" | Year{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Indicates the year of ceremony. Each year is linked to the article about the awards held that year, wherever possible.}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Recipient(s) and nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[BET|BET Social Awards]]\n| 2018\n| [[Cardi B]] & Offset\n| Baewatch\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bet.com/shows/social-awards/2018/nominees/baewatch.html |title=BET Social Awards 2018 Baewatch Nominees|website=BET|access-date=August 21, 2019}} </ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Grammy Awards]]\n| [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards|2020]]\n| \"[[Clout (Offset song)|Clout]]\" {{small|(featuring [[Cardi B]])}}\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Performance|Best Rap Performance]]\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/2020-grammy-awards-complete-nominees-list |title=2020 GRAMMY Awards: Complete Nominees List|date=November 20, 2019|website=Grammy.com|access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.yungrichnation.com/}}\n\n{{Offset (rapper)}}\n{{Migos}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Offset}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lawrenceville, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Southern hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Quality Control artists]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:African-American songwriters]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Migos members]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:FaZe Clan]]\n", "name_user": "103.255.5.102", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Offset_(rapper)"}
{"title_page": "Ballot harvesting", "text_new": "{{short description|Collecting absentee or mail-in ballots}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=December 2019|cs1-dates=l}}\n'''Ballot harvesting''',It is fraud and should be illegal mark also called '''vote harvesting''',<ref name=\":2\" /> is the collecting and submitting of [[Absentee ballot#United States|absentee]] or [[Postal voting|mail-in]] voter ballots by volunteers or workers.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/the-conversation/sd-what-is-ballot-harvesting-in-california-election-code-20181204-htmlstory.html|title=What is 'ballot harvesting' and how was it used in California elections?|first=Luis|last=Gomez|website=sandiegouniontribune.com|date=2018-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904210520/https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/the-conversation/sd-what-is-ballot-harvesting-in-california-election-code-20181204-htmlstory.html|archive-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> It occurs in some areas of the U.S. where voting by mail is common, but is illegal in some other states.\n\nArizona banned the practice except for family members and caregivers. The [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] stayed a [[Ninth Circuit Court]] ruling that overturned the ban in 2016,<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/06/us/politics/arizona-supreme-court-absentee-ballots.html | title=Arizona Can Ban 'Ballot Harvesting,' Supreme Court Says| website=nytimes.com| date=2016-11-06| last=Liptak| first=Adam|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602124715/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/06/us/politics/arizona-supreme-court-absentee-ballots.html|archive-date=2019-06-02}}</ref> and a U.S. District Court judge upheld the ban in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/05/10/judge-upholds-arizonas-ballot-harvesting-ban-democrats-vow-appeal/596855002/ |date=2018-05-10|first=Dustin|last=Gardiner|website=azcentral.com|title=Ban on 'ballot harvesting' in Arizona upheld by judge; Democrats vow to appeal}}</ref>\n\nCalifornia changed its rules before the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]] to allow persons other than family members to collect and submit ballots. Last-minute submissions of votes in the election delayed results and some argued that it altered the outcome of several elections.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.apnews.com/3cfd93f7859149809949bd611287154e | title=Democratic sweep in California raises GOP suspicion| date=2018-11-30|first1=Michael R.|last1=Blood|first2=Stephen|last2=Ohlemacher|work=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/ballot-harvesting-bounty-how-dems-used-election-law-change-to-rout-california-republicans|title=Ballot harvesting bounty: How Dems apparently used election law change to rout California Republicans|first=Andrew|last=O'Reilly|date=2018-12-03|website=foxnews.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130105602/https://www.foxnews.com/politics/ballot-harvesting-bounty-how-dems-used-election-law-change-to-rout-california-republicans|archive-date=2019-10-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/editorials/la-ed-ballot-harvesting-20181207-story.html|title=No, Republicans didn't lose in California because of ballot harvesting. But the practice is concerning|author=The Times Editorial Board|date=2018-12-07|website=latimes.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104224933/https://www.latimes.com/opinion/editorials/la-ed-ballot-harvesting-20181207-story.html|archive-date=2019-11-04}}</ref> At a ''[[Washington Post]]'' event<ref name=\":0\" /> in late November 2019<ref name=\":1\" /> (a few weeks after the elections<ref name=\":0\" />), [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] then-[[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker]] [[Paul Ryan]] said that \"California just defies logic to me\" and that his party was \"only down 26 seats the night of the election and three weeks later, [it] lost basically every California race. This election system they have\u2014I can't begin to understand what 'ballot harvesting' is.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|title=Ryan casts doubt on 'bizarre' California election results|first=Scott|last=Wong|date=2018-11-29|access-date=2019-12-20|website=thehill.com|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/418880-ryan-casts-doubt-on-bizarre-california-election-results|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214123711/https://thehill.com/homenews/house/418880-ryan-casts-doubt-on-bizarre-california-election-results|archive-date=2019-12-14}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Meanwhile, Republicans seek to improve their own use of the practice.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018We got our clocks cleaned\u2019: GOP quietly works to expand ballot harvesting in California while criticizing Democrats for the practice|first=Amy|last=Gardner|date=2019-03-14|access-date=2020-02-06|website=washingtonpost.com|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/we-got-our-clocks-cleaned-gop-quietly-works-to-expand-ballot-harvesting-in-california-while-criticizing-democrats-for-the-practice/2019/03/13/a432d902-41b7-11e9-922c-64d6b7840b82_story.html}}</ref>\n\nBallot harvesting is not legal in North Carolina.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Election fraud]] allegations related to ballot harvesting in North Carolina's [[2018 North Carolina's 9th congressional district election|9th congressional district election]] in 2018 resulted in an investigation<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/211109ea75094be396ca9a229f169060|title=Disputed House race puts spotlight on 'ballot harvesting'|first=Matt|last=Volz|date=2018-12-07|website=apnews.com}}</ref> by the [[North Carolina State Board of Elections]].<ref name=\":1\" /> On February 25, 2019, the board announced in an online press release that its five members had unanimously agreed to hold a special election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncsbe.gov/Press-Releases?udt_2226_param_detail=229|title=State Board unanimously orders new election in 9th Congressional District|author=[[North Carolina State Board of Elections]]|website=ncsbe.gov|date=2019-02-25|access-date=2020-01-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811143151/https://www.ncsbe.gov/Press-Releases?udt_2226_param_detail=229|archive-date=2019-08-11}}</ref> The [[2019 North Carolina's 9th congressional district special election]] was held as a result.<ref>[https://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/politics-government/article226864674.html Bladen County operative at center of NC election fraud investigation indicted, arrested], ''[[Charlotte Observer]]'', Ely Portillo and Jim Morrill, February 27, 2019. Retrieved April 7, 2019.</ref>\n\nVote harvesting is illegal in Texas, where state law mandates that absentee ballots cannot be sent by a person on another's behalf.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pleasantonexpress.com/articles/how-to-prevent-vote-harvesting/|title=How to prevent vote harvesting|date=2019-04-25|website=pleasantonexpress.com|first=Tom|last=Firme|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604033125/https://www.pleasantonexpress.com/articles/how-to-prevent-vote-harvesting/|archive-date=2019-06-04}}</ref> In 2013, a state bill was passed, aiming to prevent ballot harvesting by making it a misdemeanor to give or receive compensation for collecting mail-in ballots in any election.<ref>{{Cite news|title=New Voting Law Aims to Curb Ballot Harvesting|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2013/08/22/31-days-31-ways-laws-mail-ballots-takes-effect/|website=texastribune.org|last1=Aguilar|first1=Juli\u00e1n|last2=Wiseman|first2=Todd|date=2013-08-22|access-date=2020-01-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525021722/https://www.texastribune.org/2013/08/22/31-days-31-ways-laws-mail-ballots-takes-effect/|archive-date=2017-06-25}}</ref> People have been prosecuted in the state for doing it.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.realclearinvestigations.com/articles/2019/02/19/true_confessions_of_texas_vote_harvesters.html |title=True Confessions of Texas Vote Harvesters |website=RealClearInvestigations |date=February 19, 2019 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |quote=arrested twice in October on charges of vote harvesting}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Voting in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Collecting absentee or mail-in ballots}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=December 2019|cs1-dates=l}}\n'''Ballot harvesting''', also called '''vote harvesting''',<ref name=\":2\" /> is the collecting and submitting of [[Absentee ballot#United States|absentee]] or [[Postal voting|mail-in]] voter ballots by volunteers or workers.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/the-conversation/sd-what-is-ballot-harvesting-in-california-election-code-20181204-htmlstory.html|title=What is 'ballot harvesting' and how was it used in California elections?|first=Luis|last=Gomez|website=sandiegouniontribune.com|date=2018-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904210520/https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/opinion/the-conversation/sd-what-is-ballot-harvesting-in-california-election-code-20181204-htmlstory.html|archive-date=2019-09-04}}</ref> It occurs in some areas of the U.S. where voting by mail is common, but is illegal in some other states.\n\nArizona banned the practice except for family members and caregivers. The [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] stayed a [[Ninth Circuit Court]] ruling that overturned the ban in 2016,<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/06/us/politics/arizona-supreme-court-absentee-ballots.html | title=Arizona Can Ban 'Ballot Harvesting,' Supreme Court Says| website=nytimes.com| date=2016-11-06| last=Liptak| first=Adam|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602124715/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/06/us/politics/arizona-supreme-court-absentee-ballots.html|archive-date=2019-06-02}}</ref> and a U.S. District Court judge upheld the ban in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/05/10/judge-upholds-arizonas-ballot-harvesting-ban-democrats-vow-appeal/596855002/ |date=2018-05-10|first=Dustin|last=Gardiner|website=azcentral.com|title=Ban on 'ballot harvesting' in Arizona upheld by judge; Democrats vow to appeal}}</ref>\n\nCalifornia changed its rules before the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]] to allow persons other than family members to collect and submit ballots. Last-minute submissions of votes in the election delayed results and some argued that it altered the outcome of several elections.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.apnews.com/3cfd93f7859149809949bd611287154e | title=Democratic sweep in California raises GOP suspicion| date=2018-11-30|first1=Michael R.|last1=Blood|first2=Stephen|last2=Ohlemacher|work=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/ballot-harvesting-bounty-how-dems-used-election-law-change-to-rout-california-republicans|title=Ballot harvesting bounty: How Dems apparently used election law change to rout California Republicans|first=Andrew|last=O'Reilly|date=2018-12-03|website=foxnews.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130105602/https://www.foxnews.com/politics/ballot-harvesting-bounty-how-dems-used-election-law-change-to-rout-california-republicans|archive-date=2019-10-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/editorials/la-ed-ballot-harvesting-20181207-story.html|title=No, Republicans didn't lose in California because of ballot harvesting. But the practice is concerning|author=The Times Editorial Board|date=2018-12-07|website=latimes.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104224933/https://www.latimes.com/opinion/editorials/la-ed-ballot-harvesting-20181207-story.html|archive-date=2019-11-04}}</ref> At a ''[[Washington Post]]'' event<ref name=\":0\" /> in late November 2019<ref name=\":1\" /> (a few weeks after